<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 9 日星期三 05:47:33 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The Abortion Backlash Reaches Ohio]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>民主党在该州罕见的胜利显示了自<em>罗伊</em>倒台以来共和党权力的局限性。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/96KKsinuui57JYTWUFvpabh1PZU=/0x0:3600x2025/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/h_16069426/original.jpg" alt="照片显示俄亥俄州提前投票站外的“投赞成票”和“投反对票”标志" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>麦迪·麦加维 / 纽约时报 / Redux</figcaption></figure>从官方角度来看，堕胎与俄亥俄州选民今天拒绝的宪法修正案无关。这个词没有出现在选票上，堕胎法也不会因为结果而改变。<br><br>然而，从实践和政治角度来看，被称为“问题一”的投票倡议的失败全部与堕胎有关，这为生殖权利倡导者提供了自最高法院推翻<i>罗伊诉韦德案</i>以来今年一系列胜利中的最新胜利。由于担心 11 月堕胎权修正案获得通过，俄亥俄州的共和党人要求选民批准一项提案，该提案将提高州宪法修改的门槛，目前该法案需要简单多数票。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-issue-1-special-election-abortion/674923/">今天投票的措施</a>将把门槛提高到 60%。<br><br>参加夏季特别选举的俄亥俄州选民人数异常多，但选民人数有所下降。他们的决定是民主党在共和党占主导地位的州取得的罕见胜利，这表明堕胎仍然是选民进入明年总统选举的强大动力。俄亥俄州的结果可能会刺激堕胎权倡导者加大力度，通过将问题直接摆在选民面前来规避共和党控制的州立法机构。他们有理由对自己的机会感到乐观：自从最高法院对<i>多布斯诉杰克逊妇女健康组织案</i>做出裁决以来，全州范围内的堕胎权投票措施一直没有被击败，在佛蒙特州和加利福尼亚州等蓝州以及诸如此类的红州获胜。如堪萨斯州和肯塔基州。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-issue-1-special-election-abortion/674923/">阅读：下一场堕胎大战</a><br><br>去年夏天，在堪萨斯州，堕胎权一方以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2022/08/kansas-abortion-vote/671029/">18 个百分点的优势获胜，</a>令这个社会保守州的两党成员感到震惊。然而，到了俄亥俄州投票的最后一天，第一个问题的失败已不再令人意外。几周来，已经习惯了俄亥俄州失望的民主党人看到该州大城市和郊区县的提前投票人数飙升。如果共和党人希望通过将选举安排在八月的三伏天来吸引选民的注意，那么他们就打错了算盘。当我最近在该州旅行时，我在远离大城市的地区的前院和教堂外看到了<span class="smallcaps">“不投票”的</span>标志，进步的组织者告诉我，志愿者正在报名参加夏季竞选活动，其程度是闻所未闻的。反对派还包括一些独立选民和共和党选民，他们认为该提案剥夺了他们的权利。 “正是在这个‘别踩我’的时刻，选民被激活了，”俄亥俄州共同事业组织的执行董事凯瑟琳·特瑟说，该组织是一个善政倡导组织，帮助领导了击败修正案的努力。<br><br>第一个问题的反对者组建了一个两党联盟，其中包括两名前共和党州长。他们的信息重点广泛，呼吁选民“保护多数统治”并阻止立法机关公然夺权。但这次特别选举与今年秋天俄亥俄州堕胎公投的明显联系促使人们参加投票，特别是女性和年轻选民。 “选民不会花很多时间思考俄亥俄州宪法。他们可能不会花大量时间考虑投票权，”特瑟告诉我。但是，她说，“试图稀释选民的权力，从而影响对生殖权利的投票，这使得它变得非常具体，这很重要。”<br><br>去年，南达科他州和阿肯色州的选民拒绝了类似的共和党推动的让投票倡议更难通过的努力。但俄亥俄州作为一个大的前摇摆州的地位在过去十年里已经变成了红色，这对迫切希望在该州复兴本党的民主党人来说是一次独特的考验。 “我们在俄亥俄州被击败了很多次，”丹尼斯·威拉德（Dennis Willard）告诉我，他是该州的一名长期党员，也是反对派竞选活动的首席发言人。他说，共和党人试图通过这项修正案，“证明他们相信自己是不可战胜的，我们无法击败他们。”<br><br>第一个问题的失败可能为选民今年秋天保证俄亥俄州堕胎的机会扫清了道路，并且它将为进步人士开辟一条途径，以简单多数票将其他政策写入州宪法，包括大麻合法化和堕胎合法化。更高的最低工资——他们无法通过共和党控制的立法机构。包括威拉德在内的民主党人正在寻求一项修正案，以遏制曾帮助共和党锁定多数席位的不公正选区。他们还希望今晚的胜利能让俄亥俄州重新回到政治版图上。威拉德说：“我们的胜利向全国其他地区传达了一个信息，即俄亥俄州拥有可能性。” “十一月的胜利向人们表明，你不能再忽视俄亥俄州了。”<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2022/08/kansas-abortion-vote/671029/">阅读：堪萨斯州堕胎震惊事件</a><br><br>不过，目前共和党几乎没有失去对国家控制权的危险。它控制着立法机关两院的绝对多数席位；去年，共和党州长迈克·德温 (Mike DeWine) 以 25 个百分点的优势击败了民主党对手，赢得了第二个任期。一位俄亥俄州共和党人在今天的选举前匿名发言，他告诉我，第一个问题的失败和预期在 11 月通过的生殖权利修正案实际上可能会在明年对该党有所帮助，因为选民可能不再相信堕胎面临危险。在该州。 （共和党去年在纽约和加利福尼亚等蓝州表现更好，这些州的堕胎权并未受到严重威胁。）<br><br>俄亥俄州和其他类似投票措施失败的州的共和党人现在面临着他们权力的限制和选民反抗的时刻。他们会受到惩罚并重新调整，还是会继续突破界限？在确认他们失败的选票被清点之前，第一个问题的支持者不想考虑这个问题。然而，他们的批评者怀疑共和党人是否会改变他们的策略。 “他们不太可能立即停止，”特瑟说。 “要经历多次失败，他们才会明白选民不想被利用。”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 01:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-special-election-issue-1-abortion/674957/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-special-election-issue-1-abortion/674957/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[I’m Supporting Colombia Now]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>就其电动风格以及其球员为进入女足世界杯所克服的一切而言，这是理所当然的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/TWooRl9bCWX25OvfVb8kHplYDyE=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/fifa_world_cup/original.jpg" alt="哥伦比亚的琳达·凯塞多和四名牙买加球员一起参加了女足世界杯的比赛" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Asanka Brendon Ratnayake / 路透社</figcaption></figure>宿命论可能是粉丝最好的朋友。当美国女队开始本届世界杯时，我希望最好的事情发生，但我的大脑不断警告我，这支球队注定会遇到最坏的情况。令人痛苦的是，球队没有得到很好的训练，关键球员的受伤导致球队无法克服糟糕的战术。从第一场比赛开始，我观看了比赛的其余部分，寻找另一个国家，如果美国队熄火的话，我可以采用这个国家作为我自己的国家。<br><br>西班牙以其复杂的传球和时尚的控球能力引起了我的注意。作为一名亲英人士，我对英格兰队很感兴趣，直到英格兰球星劳伦·詹姆斯（Lauren James） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foxnews.com/sports/england-star-lauren-james-gets-red-card-violent-conduct-egregious-act-nigeria">鲁莽地</a>将球鞋插入倒地的尼日利亚球员米歇尔·阿洛齐（Michelle Alozie）的背部，而英格兰队则急忙缓和了进攻。但现在美国队已经退出世界杯，每个中立的善意球迷都应该热烈支持这个国家，因为它的电动风格和球员们努力克服的一切。那支球队是哥伦比亚。<br><br>尽管人们很容易赞扬<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/womens-world-cup-2023-nwsl-megan-rapinoe-alyssa-thompson/674816/">女子运动的进步</a>以及美国女性在争取同工同酬方面取得的成功，但许多国家仍然以令人震惊的方式对待她们的女运动员。哥伦比亚可以说是记录在案的最令人震惊的例子。<br><br>由于该国中场球员丹妮拉·蒙托亚的勇敢，我们对此了解很多。 2015年女足世界杯期间，她的球队晋级16强，这对于刚刚起步的哥伦比亚女足来说是一项令人难以置信的成就。她的队友不仅没有获得同工同酬，而且还未能获得同等报酬。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">据报道，他们根本没有得到</a>任何报酬，只是得到一点费用帮助。当蒙托亚向媒体抱怨时，她的国家足协拒绝了她参加 2016 年夏季奥运会的名单。后来，她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-usa-colombia/women-footballers-in-colombia-revolt-over-mistreatment-idUSKBN1QQ0F1">挥舞着</a>一名哥伦比亚足球官员的音频片段，据称解释说她因鲁莽开口而受到惩罚。<br><br>这种工资盗窃现象在哥伦比亚比赛中十分猖獗。一支女子球队，Atlético Huila，赢得了南美大陆俱乐部冠军——解放者杯。球员们被告知，他们的胜利将总共获得约 55,000 美元的奖金。但球队的奖金<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">显然被支付</a>给了一位为球队提供资金的商人。和蒙托亚一样，向媒体提出这些抱怨的球员也被排除在国家队名单之外，尽管她所施加的压力迫使俱乐部最终给了这些女性承诺的奖励。<br><br>这些事件只会增加官方的一系列不尊重行为：球员们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://assembly.malala.org/stories/colombian-womens-soccer">抱怨</a>国家足协让他们支付自己的国际航班费用，甚至不给他们买新<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-usa-colombia/women-footballers-in-colombia-revolt-over-mistreatment-idUSKBN1QQ0F1">球衣</a>。哥伦比亚俱乐部的一位有权有势的老板，同时也是该国参议院的成员，曾将女子比赛<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://as.com/futbol/2018/12/20/internacional/1545338936_774939.html">描述</a>为“女同性恋的培养皿”。<br><br>情况变得更糟。代表哥伦比亚参加国际青年锦标赛的 U-17 国家队技术总监据称虐待队内的女孩。根据 2019 年提出的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://colombiareports.com/amp/womens-football-in-colombia-harassment-blackmail-and-sexual-assault-of-minors/">指控</a>，他对这些青少年进行了不当触摸、向他们求爱，并未经他们同意进入他们的酒店房间。 （亚利桑那州立大学的一个项目“全球体育事务”在一份出色的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">报告</a>中对此进行了叙述。）再次，发声的球员被排除在国家队之外。技术总监同意认罪交易，承认减少了指控，但逃脱了牢狱之灾。<br><br>尽管如此，在今年的世界杯上，哥伦比亚女足当之无愧地击败了世界排名第二的德国队。他们刚刚淘汰了牙买加队，晋级四分之一决赛，周六他们将对阵实力耗尽的英格兰队。<br><br>哥伦比亚队令人兴奋的核心是 18 岁的攻击手琳达·凯塞多 (Linda Caicedo)，她是本届锦标赛的亮点，现在经常被誉为有潜力成为足球史上最伟大的球员之一。她可以运球击败一大群防守者，也可以用突破线的传球撕开防守。 （她对德国队的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5KdC3RiEnY4">进球</a>展现了无可挑剔的步法，是迄今为止比赛中最好的进球之一。）<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-national-team-soccer-world-cup/674885/">阅读：美国女足统治地位的终结</a><br><br>即使她没有那么才华横溢，单凭她的传记就足以令人着迷。 15岁时，她被诊断出患有卵巢癌，需要手术。尽管身患疾病且年事已高，她仍继续<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/08/02/1191392108/colombia-linda-caicedo-world-cup">批评</a>她的雇主哥伦比亚足协对待球队的恶劣态度。她的技术显然非常出色，以至于西班牙超级俱乐部皇家马德里将她转移到了迅速进步的女足球队中。尽管如此，从凯塞多的病史来看，她的脆弱感始终存在。上周，在哥伦比亚队与德国队的比赛之前，一段视频拍摄到她在训练中突然倒地，脸朝下躺在草地上，医护人员赶来救她。团队的官方解释是疲劳，但这一集抓住了崇高的完美和偶然性的结合，使凯塞多成为一个令人同情且最终不可抗拒的主角。<br><br>哥伦比亚队的表现最令人兴奋的也许是它与球迷的联系。前往澳大利亚和新西兰的哥伦比亚队伍是本届赛事规模最大、声音最大的队伍之一。这本身就是一项成就：尽管她们在途中遇到了业主和官员的阻挠，但妇女们还是成功地赢得了她们的同胞的支持。从某种意义上说，这使她们成为美国女性的真正继承人，她们在巅峰时期也凭借勇敢的行动主义和球场上的卓越表现改变了公众舆论。美国人，拥抱哥伦比亚队就像拥抱自己的球队一样。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:22:38 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-world-cup-colombia/674958/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-world-cup-colombia/674958/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Welcome to the Age of ‘Foomscrolling’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> LK-99 和 ChatGPT 引发的网络狂热揭示了技术乐观主义的复苏，以及对新技术的共同渴望，这种新技术将使我们摆脱人类的限制。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/yP3vUxT9CICFGM-CAF-gr3x3Fo4=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/lk_99_foomscroll_/original.jpg" alt="许多手机的插图，每部手机都显示一个漂浮的“LK99”肿块的图像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>我记得第一次看到漂浮的岩石时的情景。那是半夜，我面临着失眠者的困境：要不要去拿电话。我到达并打开了 Twitter——那是两周前的事了； <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-x-rebrand-juvenile-internet-style/674875/">新名字</a>还没有被人们所接受——理论上来说，滚动浏览我的提要可能会达到某种催眠效果，为睡眠创造一个机会。就在那时我看到了模糊的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://sciencecast.org/casts/suc384jly50n">视频</a>。其中，一块小而畸形的材料碎片，像铅笔折断的铅尖一样，神秘地悬浮在厚厚的抛光金属晶片上方。<br><br>我直接滚动过去。尽管关注了相当多的“纯粹的科学事物”聚合器，但在凌晨时分，我并不总是对启发感到兴奋。但几分钟后，我又看到了这个视频，然后是第三次。我注意到这不是对磁力的说教解释。这是新闻：漂浮的岩石是 LK-99，一种由韩国科学家团队合成的物质，他们认为它是一种室温环境压力超导体。<br><br>我想告诉大家，那天晚上<em>“室温常压超导体”</em>这个词对我来说很有意义，但没有。我对这句话感到困惑，就像猿猴审视着一块巨石。我寻找上下文线索。我数了数感叹号。经过几分钟的内心抵制后，我做了一些尽职调查，我的意思是轻松而睡眼惺忪地谷歌搜索。最终，通过一些努力，我了解到 LK-99 可能是材料科学家的圣杯发现。<br><br>但不仅仅是材料科学家！这与 2020 年在金星大气层中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2020/09/venus-life-phosphine-microbes/616342/">观测</a>到的磷化氢不同。如果这一发现成立（可惜<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/content/article/potential-signs-life-venus-are-fading-astronomers-downgrade-their-original-claims">事实并非如此</a>），它将强烈表明该行星上存在生命，这是一项划时代的发现，但不会改变我们的世界。室温超导体的存在不仅仅是一个关于自然的新事实。相反，根据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theconversation.com/room-temperature-superconductors-could-revolutionize-electronics-an-electrical-engineer-explains-the-materials-potential-201849">一些</a>观察家的说法，这意味着我们可以获得一种神奇的、万能的物质，它可以将我们带入一个新技术时代，电力在我们的世界中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theconversation.com/how-do-superconductors-work-a-physicist-explains-what-it-means-to-have-resistance-free-electricity-202308">毫无摩擦地</a>流动，更多的计算机是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thequantuminsider.com/2023/08/03/how-would-room-temperature-superconductors-change-quantum-computing/">量子的</a>，火车也是如此，很<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-02481-0">飘逸</a>。<br><br>鉴于 LK-99 据称是进口的，一场<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/lk99-superconductors-floating-rocks/674939/">复制韩国研究结果的</a>全球竞赛已经开始，互联网上的许多人都兴奋地观看着。中国首先到达那里的幽灵增添了一层地缘政治阴谋。 （我喜欢想象美国的材料科学家挤在一起，准备迎接他们的人造卫星时刻。） 与此同时， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/23820077/lk-99-superconductor-experts">据报道</a>韩国科学家之间也存在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newscientist.com/article/2384782-room-temperature-superconductor-breakthrough-met-with-scepticism/?utm_source=rakuten&amp;utm_medium=affiliate&amp;utm_campaign=2116208:Skimlinks.com&amp;utm_content=10&amp;ranMID=47192&amp;ranEAID=TnL5HPStwNw&amp;ranSiteID=TnL5HPStwNw-w0iN0psrMFqpajHAWVaDMA">争执</a>。每个人都可以在社交媒体上关注，惊叹于每块悬浮的岩石，就像 Twitch 观众惊叹于游戏玩家最新的击杀镜头一样。如果不出意外的话，这是一种打发时间的好方法，直到一个闪闪发光的科技乌托邦在我们周围实现。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/lk99-superconductors-floating-rocks/674939/">阅读：浮石的重要一周</a><br><br>明确地说，我所描述的是我所经历过的 LK-99 周围的氛围。最接近的类似可能是去年 11 月 ChatGPT 发布时的狂热。也许您还记得：大流行晚期的不适正在逐渐消退；人们已经准备好接受闪亮的新事物；然后，突然间，这些东西以机器人的形式出现，它们可以聊天、编码，甚至可能破坏你的婚姻。社交媒体上充斥着他们最聪明、最狡猾的攻击行为的屏幕截图<em>。</em><br><br>在 ChatGPT 发布后的几个月里，一些人开始相信正在发生“<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/foom">爆炸</a>”。在人工智能文献中，当人工智能的级联自我改进加速其自身发展，直至其变得强大到超出人类理解范围时，就会出现繁荣。 （这个词的意思是让人想起爆炸性喷发的声音。）这种特殊的、所谓的爆炸的巧妙之处在于：它是实时体验的，至少对于那些足够在线的人来说是这样。我们被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://a16z.com/2023/06/06/ai-will-save-the-world/">告知，</a>技术即将让我们摆脱痛苦和匮乏，你可以在 Twitter 上看到这一切。在特朗普担任总统期间，创造了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/doomscrolling-the-new-high-tech-way-to-slide-into-despair-11607640701"><em>“doomscrolling”</em></a>这个词来描述通过智能手机发布坏消息的习惯。这是不同的；它具有正价。称之为 fooscrolling。<br><br>并非所有新兴技术都会导致 fooscrolling。当它的非凡力量可以通过一些立即可识别的视觉形式（例如双音聊天屏幕截图或漂浮的岩石）来展示时，这种行为就更有可能发生。更重要的是，要获得 Foomscrolling 的资格，新兴技术必须是能够合理提升物种水平的技术。 （阿波罗任务会导致无休止的滚动；想象一下，<em>地出</em>照片有 100 万次转发，<span class="smallcaps">标题是我们回来了</span>。）GLP-1 受体激活药物，比如 Ozempic 中的药物，提供了一个有启发性的反例。尽管构成了人们期待已久的奇迹——一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.statnews.com/2023/08/08/novo-nordisk-wegovy-cardiovascular-risk/">有效</a>的减肥药——但它们只能解决某些问题<em>。</em>没有人发帖称这些药物最终将解决气候变化问题； Ozempic 不会提示任何人进行 fooscroll。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/06/ozempic-pills-obesity-drugs-semaglutide/674541/">阅读：再见，臭氧</a><br><br>就人工智能而言，快速滚动很快就变成了一种自嘲的东西：人工智能影响者的家庭手工业。他们支付了蓝色支票和个人简历，小心翼翼地洗白了他们之前对加密货币的热情。最初，它们很有用。该领域发展迅速，有一些行业新闻聚合器是件好事，尽管有些人容易轻信。但他们很快就声称本周令人心碎的突破清单比上周更广泛，从而压倒了讨论。这一切开始显得有点悲伤，就像 LinkedIn 一样。<br><br>也许这只是 fooscrolling 循环。最近几天，LK-99 粉丝群体一直处于不利地位。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-08-08/superconductor-lk-99-sample-may-be-available-in-weeks">通货紧缩现实主义</a>的光环已经开始为这个故事增添色彩。一些评论家声称 LK-99 只是一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/alexkaplan0/status/1688734992682086400">铁磁体</a>，科学家们已经得到消息，即使这种物质确实是室温超导体，通往<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/the-world-if">“社会将如何看待”模因</a>中描绘的未来之路也将是漫长的。一。复制声明不再是我的“为你”提要的首要内容。细微差别和清醒似乎赢得了胜利。<br><br>超导滚动的顶峰可能已经过去了。但推动它的文化欲望——对一种新工具的渴望，能够帮助我们摆脱人性的弱点，走上某种平稳的指数轨迹，通向闪闪发光和不朽的未来——看起来相当有弹性。这种集体渴望可能从奥杜瓦伊以来就以这样或那样的形式伴随着我们。互联网只是将其放大为一种探照灯。我想象它的光束很快就会找到其他东西来锁定，世界上的失眠症患者可以在夜深人静的时候用谷歌搜索一些新的东西，希望这一次，繁荣将是真实的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 20:47:40 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/foomscrolling-ai-chatgpt-lk-99-superconductor/674955/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/foomscrolling-ai-chatgpt-lk-99-superconductor/674955/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Coup in Niger Is About Power. Russia Will Exploit It.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>对尼日尔剧变最令人兴奋的解释是全球性的，而且可能是错误的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/X4FarXnxmgCdhUefxT-wrr23MFU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/niger_coup/original.jpg" alt="尼日尔的抗议者" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>法新社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>上个月底，尼日尔武装部队推翻了政府，逮捕了当选总统，并为自己夺取了权力。不久之后，一小群支持首都尼亚美政变的尼日尔人聚集在一起，表达对军政府的支持，其中一些人挥舞着俄罗斯国旗。他们普遍谴责西方，特别是前殖民国家法国。 “普京万岁！” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-news/2023/07/30/niger-pro-russian-protesters-military-coup-mohamed-bazoum/">他们高呼</a>。 “打倒法国！”<br><br>这场政变在西方各国首都引起了相当大的恐慌，这是有充分理由的。自 2020 年以来， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cfr.org/in-brief/niger-coup-could-threaten-entire-sahel">萨赫勒地区不断发生政变</a>，这是一条横跨非洲、紧邻撒哈拉沙漠、具有重要战略意义的炎热半干旱地带。 2020年，马里政府垮台。 2021年，苏丹、乍得和几内亚也发生了同样的事情。去年，布基纳法索发生政变。尼日尔被视为萨赫勒地区抵御混乱和不稳定的最后堡垒，也是最后一个政权。美国在尼日尔设有无人机基地，法国也在那里驻军，这是抵御西非圣战主义高涨的重要防线。现在，所有这一切都面临着风险。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/02/niger-europe-migrants-jihad-africa/553019/">阅读：西非危险的移民镇压</a><br><br>很少有美国人习惯于过多思考尼日尔（“你指的是尼日利亚吗？”），但今年夏天的事件似乎提供了一个鲜明的结论：亲俄罗斯的士兵推翻了亲西方的政府。民主被军事独裁连根拔起。对于任何经历过冷战的人来说，这个故事都很熟悉。尼日尔出口铀——核反应堆的重要资源——这一事实使得尼日尔的斗争更容易被理解为一场地缘政治棋局。尼日尔是一颗棋子，当地缘政治国王之间拉动棋子时，就会发生政变。因此，这场政变很快就成为一个关于美国、俄罗斯和法国的故事，而不是关于尼日尔的故事。<br><br>在解释国际新闻中的重大事件时，尤其是那些发生在陌生地点的事件时，我们都倾向于表现出地缘政治偏见，这种心态通过国际大战略的棱镜过滤每一个事件，并让每一个故事都与<em>我们</em>有关。简单化、熟悉的叙述击败了细致入微的解释，这些解释涉及很少非专业人士听说过的政治人物，他们以晦涩的缩写词和难以发音的名字而闻名。<br><br>尼日尔的军事政变已经成为耸人听闻的头条新闻和与宏大地缘政治比喻相关的政治声明的素材。乌克兰总统的一名高级顾问<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2023/8/1/russia-responsible-for-niger-coup-says-top-ukrainian-official">在没有证据的情况下坚称俄罗斯煽动了政变</a>。<em>布隆伯格</em>将这次政变报道为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2023-08-03/niger-coup-the-long-arm-of-russia-and-the-politics-of-uranium?leadSource=uverify%20wall">克里姆林宫的长臂</a>”的最新证据。 <em>《新闻周刊》</em>宣称，尼日尔的政变意味着“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newsweek.com/countdown-next-great-war-has-begun-africa-1817095">非洲下一场大战已经开始倒计时</a>”。<br><br>俄罗斯可能会因为尼日尔政变而扩大影响力（有报道称<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/niger-coup-wagner-group-junta-leaders-president-africa-regional-bloc-rcna98306">军政府正在向瓦格纳集团雇佣兵寻求帮助</a>）。但迄今为止，关于俄罗斯参与程度的猜测大多基于极其薄弱的证据——在一个面积是法国两倍的国家，在一个城市的一次抗议中，有数百人举行抗议活动，其中少数人举着俄罗斯国旗。拥有超过 2500 万人口。即使在政变之前，尼日尔的首都也是反对派的据点，因此，居住在那里的一些人举行示威以支持推翻他们厌恶的总统的士兵也就不足为奇了。<br><br>政变背后的推动力很可能是复杂、微妙的，与其说是克里姆林宫的因素，不如说是国内动态的因素。更平庸的当地事业的可能性并不能消除许多尼日尔人对法国的真正愤怒，也不能消除一些人不得不转向俄罗斯作为明显反西方的替代国际赞助商的误导性冲动。但当地媒体报道的对政变发生原因的简单解释似乎是正确的。<br><br>现任总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆一直<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-66324875">计划解雇</a>指挥精锐总统卫队的阿卜杜拉哈曼·奇亚尼将军。既然政变已经发生，奇亚尼将军不会被解雇。相反，他宣布自己是新军政府的领导人，该军政府自称为国家保卫祖国委员会。<br><br>奥卡姆剃刀的解释可能是正确的：一位即将被解雇的将军决定解雇总统。许多政变都有这样简单的起源故事，由军队内部的派系斗争以及雄心勃勃、自私自利的人引发，他们乐意将军营换成宫殿。<br><br>无论他赌博的原因是什么，奇亚尼很可能没有预料到他自掌权以来所面临的强烈反对。大多数国际参与者，包括俄罗斯，都谴责了这次政变（尽管克里姆林宫关于尊重宪法的声明最好持保留态度）。也许对奇亚尼计划最令人惊讶的威胁来自于一个主要的区域权力掮客——西非国家经济共同体。以尼日利亚为最强大成员的西非15个国家联盟对政变采取了强硬立场，甚至<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/niger-abuja-niamey-ecowas-coup-bazoum-explainer-33a6c0fa7396a90f7b78b0310ae20b32">威胁进行军事干预</a>。一些人因此将西非经共体描绘成<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://peoplesdispatch.org/2023/08/03/peoples-movements-oppose-west-backed-military-intervention-by-ecowas-in-niger/">西方的傀儡</a>，是欧美矛头的锋利末端。<br><br>再一次，一个更简单（且地缘政治方面不那么令人兴奋）的解释可能是正确的。西非国家经济共同体可能不会对这次政变采取强硬立场，因为它是一个木偶，或者因为它在意识形态上厌恶弗拉基米尔·普京；其成员国政府可能只是关心自身的自我保护。<br><br> “地区总统对军事干预感兴趣的一个原因是，他们越来越害怕自己被除掉，”伯明翰大学非洲政治专家尼克·奇斯曼教授说。 “在此之前，该地区发生了其他几起政变，他们意识到，如果他们不划清界限，他们可能就是下一个政变的受害者。”<br><br>尼日尔的政变可能并非源于大国竞争，而是源于政治和其他近在眼前的动态，但它仍然可能产生严重的国际影响。随着<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cfr.org/global-conflict-tracker/conflict/violent-extremism-sahel">圣战主义抬头</a>，萨赫勒地区的安全局势正在恶化。事实证明，过去三年上台的军政府无力与之抗衡。此外，尽管许多新的军事政权——特别是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/11/3/malian-minister-says-russia-will-ship-food-and-fuel-to-mali-in-coming-weeks">马里</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/world/burkina-faso-interim-leader-hails-russia-strategic-ally-2023-05-05/">布基纳法索</a>——已经与俄罗斯结盟，但俄罗斯政府和瓦格纳集团并没有足够的闲钱，也没有大量训练有素的军队等待部署到非洲，他们因乌克兰的惨败而陷入困境。在接下来的几个月里，萨赫勒地区的政变后政权可能会意识到，他们已经将财力雄厚且长期致力于提供外援的西方伙伴换成了一个衰弱的克里姆林宫，而克里姆林宫将不可避免地承诺过多而兑现不足。钱最终会用完。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/07/russian-disinformation-africa-food-crisis/670570/">大卫·帕特里卡拉科斯：俄罗斯的饥饿战</a><br><br>欧洲也参与其中：主要由核能提供动力的法国大约<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.lemonde.fr/en/economy/article/2023/04/24/in-niger-orano-s-giant-uranium-mine-faces-multiple-threats_6024011_19.html">10% 至 15%</a>的铀供应来自尼日尔。此外，2015年，欧盟向尼日尔政府付费，有效地建立了欧洲“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://blogs.law.ox.ac.uk/research-subject-groups/centre-criminology/centreborder-criminologies/blog/2020/05/niger-other-eu">萨赫勒边界</a>”，关闭了经尼日尔通往地中海的移民通道。政变可能会重新开放这条路线，重振以前繁荣的阿加德兹交通枢纽。美国也关心阿加德兹：美国无人机基地尼日尔 201 空军基地就位于该镇外。<br><br>如果尼日尔军政府设法继续掌权，它几乎肯定会与俄罗斯结盟。临时政权已经宣布<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/03/niger-coup-junta-joe-biden-mohamed-bazoum">取消与法国的多项军事协议</a>。但如果它向克里姆林宫示好，它就会猛然醒悟。正如马里和布基纳法索所发现的那样，俄罗斯有足够的财富来支付小规模雇佣军的费用，并满足贪婪士兵的腰包，但它还远远不够富有，无法为世界上最贫穷的国家之一的更广泛的人口提供食物。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.CD?locations=XL&amp;most_recent_value_desc=false">人均GDP</a>低于600美元的国家。<br><br>正如撒哈拉以南非洲地区经常发生的情况一样，受害者将是那些最无法忍受的人。随着士兵变身政客致富，尼日尔更广泛的民众将遭受苦难。这个故事与地缘政治无关，而是关于数百万弱势群体的普通痛苦，其墨水量将大大减少。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 17:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/niger-coup- Russia/674947/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/niger-coup- Russia/674947/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[When Small-Town Pride Sounds Like Anger]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>贾森·阿尔丁 (Jason Aldean) 说“在小镇尝试一下”庆祝社区，但它的文字和声音讲述了一个不同的故事。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1YzXZDhaMJq9PEm5-Zi9uBQNyW8=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/country_2/original.jpg" alt="乡村歌手摩根·沃伦（左）、杰森·阿尔丁（中）和卢克·库姆斯的拼贴画" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> 《大西洋月刊》的照片插图。资料来源：埃德·罗德/盖蒂；约翰希勒/盖蒂；迈克尔·洛西萨诺/盖蒂。</figcaption></figure><small><em>更新于 2023 年 8 月 8 日东部时间下午 3:52。</em></small><br><br>乡村音乐是一种具有百年历史的怀旧、传统和乡音音乐流派，其风格从未如此流行。上周，<em>公告牌</em>百强单曲榜历史上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/jason-aldean-try-that-in-a-small-town-number-one-hot-100-country-hits-top-three-1235382220/">首次</a>出现美国最受欢迎的三首乡村歌曲。对于这一里程碑的一个解释是，该流派的艺术家和观众最终<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/pro/country-music-consumption-up-2023-morgan-wallen/">倾向于</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/music/news/cmts-morgan-wallen-country-streaming-march-1235573629/">流媒体</a>：今年，乡村音乐的听众人数增长了 20%，增幅仅次于拉丁音乐和韩国流行音乐。<br><br>但这是一场值得庆祝的奇怪胜利，不仅因为上周排名第一的歌曲杰森·阿尔丁（Jason Aldean）的《在小镇尝试》（Try That in a Small Town）已被证明是一个政治热点。现在突破的曲目每首听起来都不像<em>乡村</em>音乐。这种流派总是传达出一定程度的失败者的反抗，但最近，音乐和围绕它的对话有一种明显的怨恨色彩。<br><br>在《在小镇尝试一下》中，46 岁的佐治亚州流行音乐制作人阿尔丁向所谓的乡村价值观（荣誉、邻里关系、拥有枪支）致敬，警告听众所谓的城市病态（抢劫、向警察吐口水、焚烧旗帜） ）不要乘坐某些人所说的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2016/06/a-note-about-trumpism-from-the-real-america/623689/">真正的美国</a>”。 “在这里，我们照顾自己的事情，”他夸口道。但音乐很难让人想起宁静的牧场或布满锯末的酒吧。当我听到这首歌中低沉的吉他声、低沉的小和弦以及从 Foo Fighters 的《Everlong》中摘录的即兴重复段时，我感觉自己回到了 2000 年左右的郊区男性青春期——那时我穿着一件超大的黑色连帽衫，聆听带有灵魂补丁的男人的呻吟。 Aldean 的歌曲名义上是乡村歌曲，但其声音却是后垃圾摇滚另类摇滚。<br><br> 90 年代初，Nirvana 及其同侪为一种新的主​​流男子气概开辟了空间：容易受到失败和疏远感的影响，但又带有一种硬朗、嘈杂的边缘，没有人会认为这是<em>娘娘腔</em>。很快，一群<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/07/linkin-park-chester-bennington/561713/">旋律优美的</a>乐队出现了，比如 Bush、Creed 和 Nickelback，他们剪掉了朋克风格中的垃圾摇滚，为漫无目的的焦虑创造了一个广泛吸引人的模板。现在，阿尔丁用踏板钢和右翼谈话要点更新了该模板。<br><br>你可能听说过<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/jason-aldean-donald-trump/674842/">这首歌是有争议的</a>。阿尔丁设置了一个完美的话语陷阱，利用了美国当前在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/12/historians-clash-1619-project/604093/">其自身历史的两种理论</a>之间的分裂，以及强烈反对与反对之间循环的可预测性和盈利能力。尽管这首歌没有提及种族，但许多听众在其中听到了狗哨声：阿尔丁歌词所认可的“好男孩”私刑主义在历史上一直与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2022/02/america-lynching-history-reckoning/621320/">白人至上主义暴力</a>联系在一起。他的音乐录影带包含“黑人生命也是命”抗议者的图像（尽管该片段<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2023/07/25/jason-aldean-controversial-music-video-edited/">后来被剪辑掉</a>），并在 1927 年田纳西州法院前拍摄，一名黑人在那里被私刑处决。（制作该视频的制作公司告诉<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/2023/07/20/jason-aldean-song-video-pulled-cmt-controversy/"><em>《华盛顿邮报》</em></a>说它选择了“纳什维尔以外的热门拍摄地点。”）但对这首歌的批评只会放大它：乡村音乐电视台禁止该视频后，该曲目的流媒体量<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/jul/24/jason-aldean-small-town-song-streaming-increase">猛增了 999%</a> 。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/04/jason-aldean-rearview-town-las-vegas/557876/">阅读：哀悼的音乐，无论它愿意与否</a><br><br>阿尔丁声称对他挑起的骚乱感到困惑。他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/Jason_Aldean/status/1681382697875144717?lang=en">说</a>，这首歌只是“代表了我成长过程中对社区的感受”。 （无论如何，阿尔丁是在佐治亚州梅肯市的中等城市长大的。）这种坚持，比阿尔丁声音中南方轻快的声音更能让田径运动变得<em>乡村化</em>。阿尔丁所遵循的音乐传统是蔑视城市，同时颂扬乡村的干劲。但他并没有像梅尔·哈格德（Merle Haggard）的《Okie From Muskogee》那样讽刺而勇敢地演唱，甚至不像小汉克·威廉姆斯（Hank Williams Jr.）的《乡村男孩能生存》（A Country Boy Can Survive）那样生硬自信。他也没有像<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2017/11/toby-keith-the-bus-songs/540654/">托比·基思那样</a>发出挑衅性的口号。相反，阿尔丁听起来以一种明显的后垃圾摇滚方式沉迷和恐惧——尽管他的言语表明了行动。<br><br>也许这种升华的焦虑氛围反映了歌曲背后的悲剧：美国小镇长达数十年的经济衰退。阿尔丁感叹的大城市问题—— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thirdway.org/report/the-two-decade-red-state-murder-problem">暴力犯罪</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/magazine/2022/05/23/how-my-hometown-produced-jan-6-sedition-suspect/">煽动叛乱</a>，甚至<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/10/small-town-economies-culture/543138/">社区关系破裂</a>——在许多情况下，城市外的问题比城市内更严重。这一现实是右翼怨恨的主要驱动力，而与之相关的音乐无论如何都应该带有一丝不安。阿尔丁此前以无忧无虑的乡村生活赞歌而闻名（尽管他 2018 年的单曲《后景小镇》看起来几乎像是乡村梦想的挽歌，但实际上是一首分手歌曲）。 《Small Town》的一个更好的先例是 Staind 2001 年的热门单曲《It&#39;s Been Awhile》：“已经有一段时间了/自从我能昂首挺胸以来。”并非巧合的是，斯坦德的亚伦·刘易斯现在是一位受欢迎的乡村音乐家，也是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article252897928.html">人们记忆中最有影响力的右翼抗议歌手</a>之一。<br><br>摩根·沃伦 (Morgan Wallen) 是 Nickelback 的精神之子，这也并非巧合。摩根·沃伦目前是最受欢迎的乡村音乐人，也是上周热门 100 强歌曲《最后一夜》(Last Night) 的歌手。这支加拿大摇滚乐队以朗朗上口的《How You Remind Me》和《Photograph》而闻名，经常被嘲笑<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2012/09/rahm-emanuel-saves-reputation-renounces-nickelback/323749/">为音乐平淡的终极典范</a>。但沃伦毫无歉意地指出该组织的影响力。他的首选制作人乔伊·莫伊 (Joey Moi) 制作了 Nickelback 2000 年代早期的许多热门歌曲，其中包括《Photograph》，然后与他人共同创立了 Big Loud，该公司现在是纳什维尔最热门的唱片公司之一。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/07/country-music-pandemic-protests-the-chicks-gaslighter/614092/">阅读：乡村音乐不能再隐藏它的问题</a><br><br>Wallen 是一位 30 岁的前<em>《好声音》</em>参赛者，是一位严肃的流行音乐天才，而《Last Night》（自 2 月份发行以来就引起轰动）非常出色（这也解释了为什么它取代了 Aldean 的歌曲登上了 Hot 100 的榜首）今天）。制作的层压性质以及歌手表达对自己的轻微仇恨的方式有一点五分钱乐队的品质，但“最后一夜”主要体现了纳什维尔的一种独立趋势：所谓的嘻哈、现代乡村受到说唱的影响。沃伦用轻快的吉他循环和拍手形成切分节拍，以时髦的口音唱着醉酒的争斗与和解，散发着与德雷克相同的低俗魅力。这里的讽刺是显而易见的：2021 年，沃伦被发现在镜头前说出 N 字词，这导致了一场所谓的“取消”，就像阿尔丁的那样，只会增加他的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2021/02/morgan-wallen/618137/">听众数量</a>。<br><br>上周全国排名第三的歌曲是卢克·库姆斯 (Luke Combs) 对特雷西·查普曼 (Tracy Chapman) 的《Fast Car》的演绎，也引起了一些争议。它基本上是 1988 年经典歌曲的逐字翻唱，主要区别在于库姆斯粗犷而优美的声音。上个月它在排行榜上开始上升后，一些评论员<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2023/07/13/tracy-chapman-luke-combs-fast-car-cover/">指出</a>，查普曼和其他黑人女性都没有在乡村音乐领域取得过库姆斯所享受的那种成功。这一观察激起了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/greg-gutfeld-another-week-another-country-music-star-falsely-accused-racism">保守派的不满</a>，这比最初的批评更强烈，可能会提高这首歌的受欢迎程度。正如我的同事康纳·弗里德斯多夫（Conor Friedersdorf） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/why-is-tracy-chapman-at-the-center-of-a-country-music-controversy/674794/">所说</a>，围绕这首歌的讨论表明，媒体对种族的报道可能会引发更多的混乱，而不是改革。<br><br>但要求这种注重真实性、纯美国风格的观察者避免谈论明显的事实是否站得住脚？上周乡村音乐席卷<em>Billboard</em> Hot 100 的事实是显而易见的。音乐多种多样，但表演者却不然：在阿尔丁的抗议摇滚、沃伦悠闲的说唱流和库姆斯的灵魂民谣翻唱之间，主流乡村音乐的繁荣不是源于声音，而是源于白人、男性和——至少在阿尔丁的例子中——受屈的身份。当然，所有类型都是由人口统计数据定义的。但流媒体技术，更不用说社交和政治媒体，现在奖励了煽动多元化的激情，包括播下分裂的种子。煽动斯坦对斯坦，或右对左，可以证明是有利可图的——至少在短时间内是这样（阿尔丁的歌曲今天在百强单曲榜上从第 1 名跌至第 21 名）。<br><br>其他流派的艺术家将从这一繁荣中吸取教训。就在几天前，阿尔丁出人意料地出现在纳什维尔举行的五分钱乐队音乐会上。 Nickelback 的主唱查德·克罗格 (Chad Kroeger) 从来不因其政治直言不讳而闻名。但那天晚上，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2023/08/02/jason-aldean-appears-with-brantley-gilbert-at-nashville-nickelback-concert/70511233007/">发表了讲话</a>：他说，20年来，“他们一直试图取消我们的计划。”<br><br><small><em>这个故事最初是在特雷西·查普曼的《快车》发行时被错误表述的。</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 16:10:29 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/jason-aldean-country-music-luke-combs/674952/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/jason-aldean-country-music-luke-combs/674952/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Gender War Is Over in Britain]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在维护跨性别者权利的同时，工党与激进的后现代理论划清界限。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/KyILJbm4emox0dXnrdzRLkVMDno=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/labour_horz/original.jpg" alt="性别符号交错形成一朵花" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋组织</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">当凯尔·斯塔默</span>想要改变工党在性和性别问题上的立场时，他没有发表固定演讲，也没有召开新闻发布会。相反，英国主要反对党的领导人留在了幕后，留下公众形象较低的影子部长安妮莉丝·多兹(Anneliese Dodds)在<em>《卫报》的</em>一篇简短评论专栏中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/jul/24/labour-will-lead-on-reform-of-transgender-rights-and-we-wont-take-lectures-from-the-divisive-tories">宣布了这一转变</a>。在短短800多字的时间里，她做出了三项重大宣言。一是“性别和性别是不同的”。另一个问题是，尽管工党仍然相信改变个人法定性别的权利，但仍需要采取保障措施来“保护妇女和女孩免受可能滥用该制度的掠夺者的侵害”。最后，工党因此放弃了对自我身份的承诺——即简单的在线声明就足以出于各种目的改变某人的法定性别——并将保留当前对性别不安进行医学诊断的要求。<br><br>多兹在她的文章中补充了几条解释性推文，但没有在电视上重申这一信息。第二天，工党拒绝提供发言人对 BBC 旗舰广播新闻节目发表<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m001p1nw&amp;sa=D&amp;source=docs&amp;ust=1691432639401313&amp;usg=AOvVaw1lDi1O5V-T3WeyCEmsH19B">评论</a>。尽管斯塔默最终回答了有关该主题的问题，但作为两天后更广泛<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.lbc.co.uk/news/keir-starmer-woman-adult-female-trans-labour-party/">采访</a>的一部分，总体效果是一个男人将一枚手榴弹扔在肩上，然后吹着口哨走开。<br><br>对于那些不关注英国激烈的、有时甚至是神秘的辩论的人来说，多兹的言论可能听起来没有争议，但事实并非如此。自 2015 年英国保守党政客玛丽亚·米勒 (Maria Miller) 首次提出自我身份识别以来，这种系统可能被滥用的想法就被 LGBTQ 活动人士称为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/human-interest/2021/07/wi-spa-la-transphobic-protest.html">跨性别恐惧</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/dec/15/trans-backlash-anti-gay-zealotry-section-28-homophobia">症神话</a>。因此，对单一性别运动队、更衣室和监狱的需求是“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/jul/07/cisgender-female-athletes-solidarity-trans-athletes">排他性</a>的”，类似于种族隔离和种族隔离<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newhampshirebulletin.com/2022/05/06/transgender-athletes-and-a-national-history-of-exclusionary-practices-commentary/">制度</a>下仅限白人的公共汽车、学校和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.syracuse.com/us-news/2016/05/loretta_lynch_north_carolina_bathroom_law_jim_crow_laws.html">饮水机</a>。英国左翼主要政党工党现已宣称这些论点不公平且不真实。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2023/07/29/sir-keir-starmer-labour-trans-policy-duffield-russell-moyle/">内部</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/LGBTLabour/status/1683390243733372929?s=20">异议</a>明显平息。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/nicola-sturgeon-resignation-scotland-transgender-bill/673067/">海伦·刘易斯：当政客们忽视有关性别的尖锐问题时会发生什么</a><br><br>这种转变具有更广泛的影响，尤其是在美国，性别战争双方的战斗人员都密切关注英国的辩论。 （美国的酷儿活动人士轻蔑地称这个国家为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/5050/bbc-nolan-trans-lgbtiq/">TERF岛</a>”。）工党的新立场表明，左派如何同时承认陷入困境的跨性别少数群体的需求，接受生物性别对公共政策的重要性，并寻求政治和社会利益妥协。诚然，关于该党的提议将如何在实践中发挥作用以及其威尔士和苏格兰分支机构是否会遵守，仍然存在巨大的问题。但多年来，工党一直暗中同意 LGBTQ 活动人士坚持<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mermaidsuk.org.uk/news/trans-rights-are-not-up-for-debate/">不接受任何辩论的观点</a>，但工党已经发出了严肃的民主对话开始的信号。<br><br>作为左翼政党的领导人，斯塔默发出了一个重要信号，他与激进的后现代观念划清界限，即男性和女性之间的区别是一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newstatesman.com/ideas/2023/07/the-gender-binary-debate-jacqueline-rose">社会建构</a>，生物学与女性的历史压迫无关。 （“事实上，女性并没有从属于或压迫我们的身体，”女权主义法律学者凯瑟琳·麦金农<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://signsjournal.org/exploring-transgender-law-and-politics/">最近</a>写道。“我们不需要从我们的染色体或卵巢中解放出来。”）<br><br>工党的新立场代表了一场重大的意识形态转变，但它并没有被表现为一个转变。这就是斯塔默典型的性格， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://helenlewis.substack.com/p/the-bluestocking-starmers-secret">不张扬却冷酷无情</a>。与许多美国政治家不同，他试图找到一种立场，使辩论不那么煽动，并吸引更广泛的国家而不是他的激进派基础。<br><br>自从保守党<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/sep/22/uk-government-drops-gender-self-identification-plan-for-trans-people">放弃</a>对自我认同的承诺以来的三年里，他们的一些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/tories-should-fight-next-election-29211636">政客</a>兴高采烈地抓住了性别作为文化战争问题赢得选票的潜力。相比之下，在那段时间里，斯塔默和他的部长们一直在摸索着回答<em>什么是女人？</em> ，谈论宫颈的次数远远超过妇科以外的任何人所希望的。坚持进步路线的愿望意味着工党政治家最终会<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://uk.style.yahoo.com/labour-mp-dawn-butler-child-born-without-sex-150324736.html?guccounter=1&amp;guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAGjJ3Wh5kJtAmdZI9UFHqUUB-x9ZgHcLPdrmXEL5O7fSu8yyXfQDpt_cn4aWevKWa2Ze5NrVPslU2hnSIBC1AN7F1dFHE5DMRiuxxz1hOe7vgGlGePG7YJ0UFMrxnPe7JUWf6TTd98mXd-IpbBaK9FeGagNpbRvVQMbBgUk1AdyO">说出诸如“孩子出生时没有性行为”之类令人费解的话</a>。有些人甚至因为采访者提出这个话题而攻击他们，这只会让更多人关注他们饱受折磨的答案。工党因争论拥有阴茎的女性的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.sky.com/story/keir-starmer-says-99-9-of-women-havent-got-a-penis-as-he-faces-questions-over-trans-rights-12848438">确切比例</a>而陷入困境，无法谈论英国的住房危机、高能源成本、摇摇欲坠的基础设施、糟糕的经济增长和高通胀。<br><br>如果工党普通政客愿意的话，那个时代现在已经结束了。多兹专栏发表两天后，斯塔默<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.lbc.co.uk/news/keir-starmer-woman-adult-female-trans-labour-party/">被要求</a>定义<em>女性</em>。他简单地回答：“成年女性。”如果左翼圈子允许这个答案，那么采访者就不会再提出一个简单的陷阱问题，工党就可以回去谈论经济并试图赢得中间选民的支持。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">由于担心伤害</span>跨性别者或与彻头彻尾的偏执者结盟，一些左翼人士避免表达对自我认同等政策的疑虑，并且在过去十年中，工党活动人士对那些发声的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/labour-officials-quit-in-transgender-row-06qtj2b3r">女权主义评论员</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/f/wpuk-fringe-report">进行</a>了诽谤。斯塔默现在扩大了讨论的范围。在整个欧洲，医学协会建议<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/texas-puberty-blockers-gender-care-transgender-rights/673941/">谨慎</a>对待所谓的未成年人性别关怀平权模式。<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/content/376/bmj.o629/rr-1">医生们</a>正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.academie-medecine.fr/la-medecine-face-a-la-transidentite-de-genre-chez-les-enfants-et-les-adolescents/?lang=en">讨论</a>社会传染可能影响青少年公开身份的可能性，以及至少在某些情况下，青春期本身可以解决性别焦虑的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/company/newsroom/gender-dysphoria-in-young-people-is-rising-and-so-is-professional-disagreement/">建议</a>。缺乏青春期阻滞剂安全性或有效性的证据已<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/content/bmj/380/bmj.p697.full.pdf">成为</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20230208-sweden-puts-brakes-on-treatments-for-trans-minors">可说的事实</a>。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/texas-puberty-blockers-gender-care-transgender-rights/673941/">海伦·刘易斯：摆脱儿童性别文化战争的唯一出路</a><br><br>在体育领域，国际机构正在废除之前让跨性别女性与出生女性运动员竞争的政策。最新改变规则的组织是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/sports/british-rowing-ban-transgender-athletes-womens-events-telegraph-2023-08-02/">英国赛艇协会</a>，该组织将女子赛事仅限于生理上的女性，同时还为变性人的参与设立了类别。两周前，自行车运动的世界管理机构国际自行车联盟将女性类别<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.skysports.com/more-sports/other-sports/news/15264/12921233/uci-to-ban-transgender-women-from-participating-in-female-cycling-events-under-new-policy#:~:text=The%20policy%20created%20an%20'open,yet%20to%20begin%20hormone%20therapy.">限制</a>为从未服用过睾酮的女性参赛者，同时还为任何经历过男性青春期或服用过男性激素的人设立了“公开”竞赛。<br><br>然而在美国，政治两极分化正在冻结一场毫无成果的讨论。关于这个主题的写作最令人沮丧的方面之一是许多自由主义者不知道他们不知道什么。红色州的惩罚性禁令，加上共和党公开的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/ron-desantis-cnn-interview/674751/">反 LGBTQ 言论</a>，使得民主党人本能地为青春期阻滞剂和未成年人性别手术辩护，尽管欧洲专家变得更加谨慎。尽管海外同事对证据基础存有疑虑，但医疗团体仍坚持平权模式，这一事实阻碍了关于美国儿童过渡的适当的、基于证据的辩论。美国儿科学会董事会刚刚<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/03/health/aap-gender-affirming-care-evidence-review.html">一致投票决定</a>暂时继续支持肯定性做法。<br><br>显然，存在广泛的中间立场。去年年底进行的民意调查显示，约四分之三的美国人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2023/05/05/trans-poll-gop-politics-laws/">反对</a>在住房、大学、工作场所和获得医疗保险方面对跨性别者的歧视。但超过 60% 的美国成年人还认为，跨性别女性和女孩不应该参加任何级别的女性运动，并且绝大多数人也反对对 18 岁以下青少年进行激素治疗。即使在跨性别成年人中，同一项民意调查也发现十分之三的人支持体育运动中基于性别的限制，同样的数字表示年幼的孩子接受青春期阻滞剂是不合适的。 （发表这项民意调查的<em>《</em><em>华盛顿邮报》</em>指出，这项民意调查是在数百项限制医疗保健和体育参与的红州法案出台之前进行的。）似乎大多数美国人都乐于在日常生活中支持跨性别者，而还相信跨性别女性与其他女性并不相同，这意味着所有这些。但双方的精英都很少明确表达这一立场。 “这不仅仅是部落主义；这是极端主义，”作家丽莎·塞林·戴维斯告诉我。 “这是两党制度，每一党都迎合其最激进的选民。当然，这也是社交媒体的故事。”<br><br>戴维斯作为一个男性化女儿的父母来到了美国的性别辩论中。当她在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/18/opinion/my-daughter-is-not-transgender-shes-a-tomboy.html"><em>《纽约时报》</em></a>上写下这段经历时，她收到了一封信，敦促她让她的“儿子”变性，并警告“他”否则可能会自杀身亡。她仍然认为自己属于左派，但相信她的天然盟友已经失去了远见。 “就民主党而言，他们投入了如此多的政治资本来支持一些事情，这些事情不仅可能对大多数民主党选民来说并不重要，而且我认为可能有点令人反感，”她告诉我。 “声称支持变装皇后故事时间，而不是 25 美元的最低工资，这真的很愚蠢。”<br><br>戴维斯尤其感到沮丧的是，民主党并没有让那些在性别问题上背离党的正统观念的立法者的日子好过。德克萨斯州黑人女性民主党州众议员肖恩·蒂埃里 (Shawn Thierry) 在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.houstonchronicle.com/politics/texas/article/houston-democrat-transgender-care-ban-18100564.php">支持</a>一项限制 18 岁以上人群接受性别相关激素疗法的共和党法案后，面临谴责动议和主要挑战。她的民主党同事指责她重复共和党的谈话要点，但她坚称她查看了证据并发现证据不足。她的批评者也对她在投票前会见了两名脱节者感到不满。想象一下，一位立法者因听取对正在讨论的问题有个人经验的人的意见而受到批评。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/detransition-transgender-nonbinary-gender-affirming-care/672745/">Daniela Valdes 和 Kinnon MacKinnon：认真对待脱转变剂</a><br><br>偏离共和党路线也会招致猛烈的抵制。 2021年，时任阿肯色州州长阿萨·哈钦森否决了一项儿童性别保健法案，招致<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/meetthepressblog/tucker-carlson-asa-hutchinson-tussle-transgender-rights-vaccines-rcna94305">塔克·卡尔森</a>和该州的批评。但哈钦森给出了一个令人信服的理由：他反对对未成年人进行手术，但认为该法案违宪并剥夺了父母的权利。 （他的否决被推翻，但该法律后来被法官<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/judge-strikes-gender-affirming-care-ban-arkansas/story?id=100257964">推翻</a>。）今年早些时候，犹他州州长斯宾塞·考克斯在与受这一变化影响的家庭会面<em>后才</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.yahoo.com/disagree-better-utah-governor-wants-143000349.html">批准了</a>对该州过渡性护理的限制，他告诉记者：“如果如果你不愿意坐下来倾听跨性别儿童及其家人的意见，那么你可能会以错误的方式制定政策。”考克斯现在利用担任全国州长协会主席的一年来推动一项名为“Disagree Better”的倡议。<br><br>在英国，斯塔默打赌大多数选民会感激地接受他提出的妥协方案——这一方案既能缓解他们的担忧，又能缓解辩论的激烈程度。工党也向跨性别活动人士做出了让步，提出了一个系统，允许患者从家庭医生那里得到烦躁不安的诊断，而不必向匿名小组提出申请。迄今为止，斯塔默拒绝代表工党向因工党现在正式认同的观点而受到骚扰的女权主义者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/07/25/keir-starmer-owes-rosie-duffield-an-apology/">道歉</a>。<br><br>坦率地说，我们需要将其视为一个棘手但平凡的问题来解决，而不是攻击反对派的情感手段。这是让美国人关于性别的对话更像英国的唯一方法。民主党需要会见非变性者，共和党需要会见变性活动人士。双方都需要听取对手论点的最佳版本，并确保辩论是在现有最佳证据的基础上进行的。除了任何证据审查之外，戴维斯还希望建立一个关于儿童性别护理的两党委员会。 “最好的办法就是停止战斗并获取数据，”她说。<br><br>在那之前，左派必须能够捍卫跨性别者的权利，同时又不否认男性和女性之间有意义的差异。右翼必须能够在不妖魔化跨性别者的情况下表达担忧。自由派和保守派都应该停止向尽力而为的父母指责虐待儿童。如果广泛、宽容的中间派能够坚持自己的立场，那么性别战争就可以结束。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/uk-trans-rights-labour-party/674944/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/uk-trans-rights-labour-party/674944/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Local-News Crisis Is Weirdly Easy to Solve]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>恢复过去 20 年来失去的新闻工作岗位不仅成本低廉，而且会收回成本。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/OxjtWxqBQ3MegS-BPLwSTdRukEI=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/local_news_final_horz/original.jpg" alt="装满钱的报刊箱" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/《大西洋月刊》插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>扎克<span class="smallcaps">·波德莫尔</span>并没有打倒腐败的市长。他没有发现秘密酷刑场所或揭露强大宗教机构的虐待行为。但他在 2019 年作为<i>《盐湖论坛报》</i>记者撰写的这篇文章改变了我对当地新闻价值的看法。<br><br>波德莫尔当时是《<i>论坛报》</i>的记者，也是我共同创办的非营利组织“美国报告”的一名成员，他发表了一篇报道， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sltrib.com/news/2019/07/28/san-juan-county-paid/">揭露</a>犹他州圣胡安县向一家律师事务所支付了数十万美元的游说费。 Podmore 发现该公司向该州最贫困的县多收了 109,500 美元的费用。在他的故事的刺激下，该公司偿还了这笔钱。也许是因为它涉及的不是数十亿美元，而是一个更容易想象的数字，这让我震惊：在一个故事中，波德莫尔为县里收回了一笔相当于他年薪三倍的金额。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/11/alden-global-capital-killing-americas-newspapers/620171/">摘自 2021 年 11 月号：一家神秘的对冲基金正在摧毁新闻编辑室</a><br><br>您可能读过过去二十年当地新闻的崩溃。平均每周有两家报纸<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://localnewsinitiative.northwestern.edu/research/state-of-local-news/report/">停刊</a>。大约 1,800 个曾经有本地新闻的社区现在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usnewsdeserts.com/reports/news-deserts-and-ghost-newspapers-will-local-news-survive/the-news-landscape-in-2020-transformed-and-diminished/">没有了</a>。许多仍悬而未决的报纸被迫用骨干员工勉强度日，因为它们的所有者（通常是私募股权公司）寻求削减成本。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2021/07/13/u-s-newsroom-employment-has-fallen-26-since-2008/">皮尤研究中心的一项研究</a>显示，从 2008 年到 2020 年，报纸新闻编辑室的员工数量下降了 57%，导致数千份“幽灵报纸”几乎无法覆盖其社区。<br><br>在过去的 15 年里，我一直致力于扭转这一趋势。这意味着我已经习惯于谈论新闻荒漠对美国民主构成的威胁。毕竟，民主自治的整个概念取决于人民了解公职人员在做什么。 That&#39;s impossible without a watchdog press. Researchers have linked the decline of local news to decreased voter participation and higher rates of corruption, along with increased polarization and more ideologically extreme elected officials. At this point, I can make high-minded speeches about this stuff in my sleep, with Thomas Jefferson quotes and everything. Recently, however, I&#39;ve come to realize that I have been ignoring a less lofty but perhaps more persuasive argument: Funding local news would more than pay for itself.<br><br> Unlike other seemingly intractable problems, the demise of local news wouldn&#39;t cost very much money to reverse. Journalists are not particularly well compensated. Assuming an average salary of $60,000 (generous by industry standards), it would cost only about $1.5 billion a year to sustain 25,000 local-reporter positions, a rough estimate of the number that have disappeared nationwide over the past two decades. That&#39;s two-hundredths of a percent of federal spending in 2022. I personally think this would be an amount well worth sacrificing to save American democracy. But the amazing thing is that it wouldn&#39;t really be a sacrifice at all. If more public or philanthropic money were directed toward sustaining local news, it would most likely produce financial benefits many times greater than the cost.<br><br> What do government officials do when no one&#39;s watching? Often, they enrich themselves or their allies at the taxpayers&#39; expense. In the 2000s, some years after its local paper shut down, the city of Bell, California, a low-income, overwhelmingly Latino community, raised the pay of the city manager to $787,637 and that of the police chief to $457,000. The <i>Los Angeles Times</i> eventually <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.latimes.com/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715-story.html">exposed</a> the graft, and several city officials ended up in prison. Prosecutors accused them of costing taxpayers at least $5.5 million through their inflated salaries. These salaries were approved at municipal meetings, which is to say that if even one reporter (say, with a salary of $60,000) had been in attendance, the city might have saved millions of dollars.<br><br> Sometimes the work of journalists prompts government investigations into the private sector, which, in turn, produce fines that go into the public&#39;s bank account. After the <i>Tampa Bay Times</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tampabay.com/investigations/2022/05/09/tampa-bay-times-reporters-win-pulitzer-prize-for-poisoned-series/">found</a> that a battery recycler was exposing its employees and the surrounding community to high levels of lead and other toxins, regulators fined the company $800,000. A ProPublica <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/sec-issues-more-fines-over-magnetar-deals-and-appears-to-move-on">investigation</a> into one firm&#39;s questionable mortgage-backed securities prompted investigations by the Security and Exchange Commission, which ultimately assessed $435 million in fines. A review of more than 12,000 entries in the Investigative Reporters and Editors Awards found that about one in 10 triggered fines from the government, and twice as many prompted audits.<br><br> In other cases, local-news organizations return money directly to consumers by forcing better behavior from private institutions. MLK50, a local newsroom in Memphis, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/what-happens-after-a-debt-collection-machine-grinds-to-a-halt">teamed up</a> with ProPublica to report that Methodist Le Bonheur Healthcare had sued more than 8,300 people, many of them poor, for unpaid hospital bills. In response, the faith-based institution erased nearly $12 million in debt.<br><br> Of course, most journalism does not convert quite so immediately into cash on hand. The impacts may be enormous but indirect. One study of toxic emissions at 40,000 plants <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0095069616301371">found</a> that when newspapers reported on pollution, emissions declined by 29 percent compared with plants that were not covered. The study did not track the ripple effects, but it stands to reason that residents in the less polluted areas would have fewer health problems, which in turn would translate to lower medical costs and less lost work time. Another <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3175555">study</a> , by the scholars Pengjie Gao, Chang Lee, and Dermot Murphy, looked at bond offerings in communities with and without local news from 1996 to 2015. It concluded that for each bond offering, the borrowing costs were five to 11 basis points higher in the less covered communities. That translated to additional costs of $650,000 an issue, on average.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/05/local-news-media-trust-americans/618895/">Amanda Ripley: Can the news be fixed?</a><br><br> One academic tried to track the economic effects even further downstream. In his book <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/democracy-s-detectives-the-economics-of-investigative-journalism-james-t-hamilton/9780674545502?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Democracy&#39;s Detectives: The Economics of Investigative Journalism</i></a> ,<i> </i>the Stanford professor James Hamilton looked at a series by KCBS in Los Angeles that uncovered a flawed restaurant-inspection program. The exposé prompted LA County to require restaurants to display their inspection scores, which in turn led to a 13.3 percent drop in LA County hospital admissions for food poisoning. Hamilton estimated a savings of about $148,000. In another case study, Hamilton analyzed a series by the Raleigh <i>News &amp; Observer</i> that found that, because the state criminal-justice system didn&#39;t adequately keep track of those under supervision, 580 people on probation in North Carolina killed someone from 2000 to 2008. After the state implemented reforms, murders committed by people on probation declined. Applying the statistical “value of human life” used by the US Department of Transportation, Hamilton concluded that society saved about $62 million in just the first year after the policy changes. The series cost only about $200,000 to produce.<br><br> Ideally, investment in local news would come from the federal government, which has more freedom to think long-term than cash-strapped states and municipalities do. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rebuildlocalnews.org/">The Rebuild Local News coalition</a> , of which I am president, supports legislation that would provide a refundable tax credit for news organizations that employ local reporters, and a tax break for small businesses that advertise in local news. A <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rebuildlocalnews.org/community-news-small-business-support-act/">new version</a> of the bill was just introduced in the House of Representatives by the Republican Claudia Tenney and the Democrat Suzan DelBene. Civic-minded philanthropists focused on high-impact donations should also put money into local news, given the likely societal returns. It&#39;s impossible to quantify exactly how much money would be generated for government and consumers by restoring the health of local news. But it&#39;s nearly as hard to deny that the investment would pay off handsomely. And the saving-democracy part? Well, that&#39;s just gravy.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/local-news-investment-economic-value/674942/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/local-news-investment-economic-value/674942/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trees? Not in My Backyard.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A story about three trees, an angry “community,” and power in Washington, DC <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/C3iRoI6hkPEQlcPImgJS1xlo8hU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/xenia_trees_2/original.jpg" alt="The root of a tree, with a map drawn all over it and red points" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Joanne Imperio / The Atlantic. Sources: Getty; Library of Congress.</figcaption></figure> “I <span class="smallcaps">t&#39;s almost like</span> the government&#39;s imposing its will on its residents,” Trayon White, the DC council member for Ward 8, said at the council&#39;s June 6 legislative meeting. He wasn&#39;t talking about a proposed highway, a subway station, a power plant, or— <em>perish the thought</em> —an apartment building. He was talking about trees: specifically, three linden trees on Xenia Street planted a few years ago by DC&#39;s Urban Forestry Division. To my surprise, the legislative body of a major American city experiencing escalating <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2023/05/05/dc-homeless-annual-count/">homelessness</a> and a serious spike in violent <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mpdc.dc.gov/page/district-crime-data-glance">crime</a> dedicated a quarter of its time that day to discussing three trees.<br><br> White said he was concerned about the potential risk to property values and what he sees as a “reasonable fear” that once mature, the trees would “be large enough to make it difficult to see through and around the walkway, which is a public-safety concern.” He asked his colleagues to support an emergency resolution to remove them before this happened.<br><br> For a while, the members carried on as though this were a perfectly normal matter for their attention. A few suggested that perhaps expanding the tree canopy was good, actually. But no one really questioned the underlying premise of White&#39;s proposal: that the community had risen up in dendrophobic opposition.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/07/social-trees-meg-lowman-suzanne-simard/619015/">From the July/August 2021 issue: A better way to look at trees</a><br><br> “We want to note that these are homeowners who are worried about the value of their homes,” White said. “I just believe that [the District Department of Transportation, or DDOT] can be more friendly in responding to the needs of the community with their request, and if they&#39;re requesting different trees, I don&#39;t see what the big problem is.”<br><br> The council went on to debate the merits of the public-safety question. Councilman Kenyan McDuffie recalled that in his ward the city had planted trees in parking spaces so as not to encroach on the already narrow sidewalks. “I still question whether there is the appropriate level of consultation and engagement in the impacted communities,” he said, backing White.<br><br> After more than 20 minutes, the chair of the council noted with surprise that “we spent this much time on the issue of removing three trees.” White, recognizing the lack of sufficient support from his colleagues, withdrew the matter from the agenda, allowing the trees to grow another day.<br><br> What initially drew me to this story was the obvious mismatch between the rhetoric at the council meeting and the subject at hand. How could a few trees constitute a threat to public safety or property values? Were these trees particularly ugly? And <em>who</em> was behind White&#39;s push to get them removed? Like many stories about government, this seemingly trivial drama turned out to be about power, and how people justify using it.<br><br> X <span class="smallcaps">enia Street</span> is in Ward 8, physically separated from most of DC by the Anacostia River. That&#39;s not the only thing that sets it apart. This side of the river is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://censusreporter.org/profiles/61000US11008-ward-8-dc/">overwhelmingly Black</a> and has a higher unemployment rate, a lower labor-force-participation rate, and a higher poverty rate than the rest of the city. The census tract that contains Xenia Street is one of the most heat sensitive in the city, a metric that reflects the prevalence of asthma, coronary heart disease, and disability, as well as racial demographics and income. DC&#39;s Urban Forestry Department, a division of DDOT, planted the trees after a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aphis.usda.gov/aphis/resources/pests-diseases/hungry-pests/the-threat/emerald-ash-borer/emerald-ash-borer-beetle#:~:text=The%20Emerald%20Ash%20Borer%20(Agrilus,hidden%20in%20wood%20packing%20materials.">beetle infestation</a> harmed several local ash trees. A senior official told me the department is generally concerned about the unequal distribution of tree canopy across wards: At the end of June, Ward 8 had roughly 500 open requests for new plantings; the higher-income Ward 4 had nearly 6,000.<br><br> Tree planting doesn&#39;t meet the bar for more serious types of notification and community-input processes that a new road or train station might. But according to Kay Armstead, a former member of the Advisory Neighborhood Commission—an elected body meant to serve as a hyperlocal voice on zoning, bike lanes, liquor licenses—the city did inform the commission of a plan to bring more trees to the neighborhood. In the fall of 2020, it planted 35 trees, some American linden, some apple, on a publicly owned lot between two condo buildings, 450 Xenia Street and 450 Condon Terrace.<br><br> I wanted to see the trees for myself. In the weeks following White&#39;s proposed emergency resolution, I visited the quiet residential street on three separate occasions, asking people if they had any thoughts about the trees. No one I interviewed registered strong opinions, or had even heard of the controversy.<br><br> One resident of 450 Condon Terrace immediately redirected my attention to a massive hole in the ground of her parking lot, which she said had been caused by a garbage truck. Another told me he hadn&#39;t heard about the controversy but wanted to talk about trash pickup. “I mean, look at this shit,” he said, pointing to a pile of trash on the sidewalk. Trees? Low on the list of priorities. Another man found my line of questioning confusing, to say the least. “They&#39;re oxygen!” When I said some people worried the trees could encourage crime, he laughed at me. “Now, you know that&#39;s crazy. Who&#39;s going to hide underneath these trees?”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/10/big-little-ideas-start-planting-trees/622142/">James Fallows: Start planting trees</a><br><br> So who forms “the community” so opposed to the trees? His name is Darryl Ross.<br><br> Ross has been active in local politics for decades. He is treasurer of the Ward 8 Democrats and of White&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/just-a-quarter-of-dc-constituent-service-funds-provided-assistance-report-finds/2019/03/26/191d0f80-4fc8-11e9-88a1-ed346f0ec94f_story.html">constituent-services fund</a> , a controversial purse that some critics have called a “slush fund.” When White refers to constituent outreach to his office over this issue, he&#39;s talking about Ross. (White and his chief of staff both declined to be interviewed for this story.) Ross doesn&#39;t live at 450 Xenia Street, but he used to. He still owns a unit in the building, which he rents out, and is the president of the Xenia Condominium Owners Association.<br><br> Ross has been angry about the trees since the day they were planted. He told me he saw workers digging and began calling around, furious that no one had informed the neighborhood about the project, astounded that the city thought 35 trees (“a forest!”) made sense on the street, and frustrated by hypothetical future private costs that the trees would impose on residents.<br><br> His 311 requests to remove the trees went nowhere. So he tried officials at DDOT and the Urban Forestry Department, White and several other members of the city council, the office of the inspector general, and current and former members of the Advisory Neighborhood Commission. He knows he wouldn&#39;t have been able to get so much attention without his connections: “Believe me, I&#39;m using all the leverage I can to get the desired result,” he told me.<br><br> After months of effort, in August of 2021, representatives from DDOT, White&#39;s chief of staff, and a senior staffer for at-large Council Member Anita Bonds met with Ross and a couple of area residents on the site to discuss the problem. The officials agreed to remove 14 of the 35 newly planted trees. The agency also promised to complete a lighting survey, which resulted in the installation of three large streetlights, a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://urbanlabs.uchicago.edu/projects/crime-lights-study">data-driven approach to reducing crime</a> .<br><br> The “desire to compromise for this individual is because we want to make sure we&#39;re doing this <em>for</em> people, not <em>to</em> them,” a senior official in the Urban Forestry department (who requested anonymity to speak freely) told me. “If we can mollify someone, engender a sense of ownership … You take someone and make them more of an ally.”<br><br> Ross was not mollified. He continued his crusade to have three more trees removed—the ones closest to his condo building&#39;s walkway. He lodged a complaint with DC&#39;s Office of the Inspector General, which led to a formal response from DDOT Director Everett Lott, who argued that the department had broken no laws in planting the trees and had in fact exceeded the mandate for public notification. Undeterred, Ross continued his advocacy, which culminated with White&#39;s proposed emergency resolution at the city-council meeting in June.<br><br> Ross put me in touch with a few of his allies, most of whom sounded only slightly more informed about the situation than the residents I randomly encountered on my visits. Some had no idea that many trees had already been removed; others were just vaguely aware that at one point the trees had seemed like a problem. One woman told me she thought children might throw fallen apples at cars or building windows. (The trees at issue in the emergency legislation are linden, not apple.)<br><br> According to Ross, the condo association was united in opposition. He called the vice president, Hazel Farmer, on speaker in my presence.<br><br> “You remember there were four [trees] that were too close to the walkway?” he asked.<br><br> “I thought we had finished that,” she said, sounding confused.<br><br> “No, no, we are still battling,” Ross replied quickly.<br><br> After Ross refreshed her memory, Farmer said she worried that the trees would one day push up the concrete sidewalk, impeding residents&#39; ability to walk in and out of the building. Ross later clarified that Farmer had already moved out because the steps on the walkway were too difficult for her to navigate.<br><br> I <span class="smallcaps">na July legislative meeting,</span> White withdrew the emergency resolution, citing a compromise reached by the chair of the DC council and DDOT to apply a growth regulator to the offending saplings. This outcome infuriates Ross, who is seeking a meeting with Mayor Muriel Bowser: “At the end of the day we voted for her, we didn&#39;t vote for [DDOT officials], and we had faith in her to do what&#39;s best for the people.”<br><br> Ross still has options. If the worst happens and these trees end up extending over the sidewalk, he can call 311 to request tree pruning. According to the Urban Forestry Department, these requests are resolved, on average, within 20 days.<br><br> But the more I talked with Ross and his allies, the more I realized that the trees were also stand-ins for their broader unhappiness with DDOT, which they see as not acting <em>for</em> them but doing things <em>to</em> them: bike racks “just dropped” in front of some businesses, bike lanes constructed over their objections, and traffic-safety infrastructure— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.arcgis.com/apps/dashboards/a2f1cca5159e4c6eae197895d2e08336">in DC&#39;s highest traffic-fatality ward</a> —installed without their consent. This is why Ross was able to enlist supporters in the first place—by tapping into existing anger some residents feel toward the city&#39;s transportation agency. Anger that, in a ward of nearly 90,000 people, a few individuals do not have the final say.<br><br> This is a classic story of local government and its discontents. Government takes action. Angry, well-connected local fights back, annoyed that they weren&#39;t consulted. But when they fight back, claiming the will of the “people,” how do we know if they&#39;re right? Backing up a bit: How do we even decide who the people <em>are</em> ?<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/local-government-power-nimby-denver/674164/">From the July/August 2023 issue: Colorado&#39;s ingenious idea for solving the housing crisis</a><br><br> In the Xenia Street episode, is it the people who live right next to the trees? How about one street over? Just property owners like Ross? Because the trees are on public land, should all DC residents have a say? Is it all Americans? Addressing the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2022/07/25/biden-harris-administration-announces-plans-reforestation-climate#:~:text=WASHINGTON%2C%20July%2025%2C%202022%20%E2%80%94,trees%20over%20the%20next%20decade.">reforestation backlog is a national priority</a> . Or, given that trees help mitigate climate change, should <em>all</em> people have a voice? This is the so-called boundary problem, which the political scientist Robert Dahl once quipped has “no theoretical solution,” only pragmatic ones. Even if surveying all of humanity were theoretically desirable, it&#39;s a practical impossibility. One has to draw the line somewhere and delegate representatives or spokespersons.<br><br> Arguably the best delegates in this matter are local elected officials, who get their authority from voters. The problem is that, at the local and especially hyperlocal levels, nobody&#39;s voting. In 2018, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonblade.com/2018/08/17/two-thirds-of-d-c-neighborhood-races-uncontested/">two-thirds of Advisory Neighborhood Commission races were uncontested</a> . Even when these contests are competitive, only a handful of people show up to cast a ballot. In the single-member district that includes Xenia Street, Armstead, one of Ross&#39;s allies, lost her election <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://electionresults.dcboe.org/election_results/2022-General-Election">137–91</a> . Last year, two ANC races were <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://dcist.com/story/22/12/01/two-dc-races-to-be-decided-by-casting-of-lots/">tied following Election Day</a> ; in one of them each candidate had garnered 12 votes apiece, while in the other each candidate had claimed just one (presumably their own). Vox populi indeed.<br><br> If the ANC can&#39;t quite speak for the people, what about the DC council, and specifically Council Member White? Council voting rates are also dismal: About 8,700 people total voted in the 2020 primary contest that secured White&#39;s reelection, out of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://data.census.gov/table?q=B29001:+CITIZEN,+VOTING-AGE+POPULATION+BY+AGE&amp;g=040XX00US11%246100000_1400000US11001000101&amp;tid=ACSDT5Y2021.B29001">roughly 57,000 citizens of voting age in Ward 8</a> .<br><br> How about DDOT? As an agency housed in the executive branch, DDOT gains its authority from the mayor. In 2022, Mayor Bowser received fewer than 4,000 votes from Ward 8 during the primary (the true election in this heavily Democratic city). Only about 10,000 people in the ward voted at all in that contest.<br><br> There&#39;s no magical threshold at which elected officials become democratically legitimate. But more than half of eligible voters <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2023/2022-voting-registration.html#:~:text=Turnout%20rates%20for%20the%20citizen,%25)%20citizen%20voting%2Dage%20population.">routinely show up</a> for federal and state contests while our municipal elections <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.whovotesformayor.org/">struggle to top 15 percent</a> . What we&#39;re seeing in local governments is a crisis of democracy unparalleled at other levels of government.<br><br> “I <span class="smallcaps">t&#39;s not the trees;</span> it&#39;s the disrespect,” Armstead told me. She called tree removal a top priority because “when you come to a community and you don&#39;t listen, then [we&#39;re] being disrespected and disregarded.” Ross made a similar point: “It makes me angry because, like I said, we&#39;re the stakeholders. We&#39;re the taxpayers. We fund the salaries for the DC government employees, council … This is our money!”<br><br> When we collectively feel entitled to hold the government accountable, that&#39;s democracy. But when individuals do, that&#39;s something else: institutional capture.<br><br> Because so few people vote in local elections, the power of those who speak up and claim to speak for their neighborhoods is hard to challenge. If a homeowner&#39;s association headed by the neighborhood busybody says he speaks for you, are you showing up to contest that claim? What&#39;s obvious about Ross&#39;s perseverance is that its effectiveness is largely due to its singularity. If <em>everyone</em> engaged as he did—called and emailed and attended meeting after meeting, filed complaints with everyone from the office of the inspector general on down—his power would dilute instantly. No one can claim to speak for a community if everyone&#39;s speaking for themselves.<br><br> Democracy is about feedback loops. We elect people. If they do poorly, we choose alternatives. But when the election system falters from disuse, other feedback loops take root. Elected officials at the local level become accountable to the unrepresentative handful of voters who do engage; and public servants become preemptively sensitive to well-connected people who have the time and energy to demand disproportionate focus.<br><br> People like Ross may not get everything they want, but they know how to command attention. No fewer than four DC council members have become personally involved in the matter of the trees on Xenia Street. Meanwhile, that massive hole in the ground? It&#39;s still there.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trees-xenia-street-washington-dc-local-government/674949/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trees-xenia-street-washington-dc-local-government/674949/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Killer Apps]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Is social media making America&#39;s murder surge worse? <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/BsZBNpGQ7buWlTQSboDFdaRRL8Q=/258x0:1259x1251/648x810/media/img/2023/08/01/DIS_McGillis_InstaViolence/original.jpg" alt="A hand pointing a gun whose muzzle is shaped like the Instagram logo" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Erik Carter</figcaption></figure> <small><i data-stringify-type="italic">This article was featured in One Story to Read Today, a newsletter in which our editors recommend a single must-read from</i> The Atlantic <i data-stringify-type="italic">, Monday through Friday.</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sign up for it here.</a></i></small><br><br> O <span class="smallcaps">ne fall evening in 2020</span> , Jarell Jackson and Shahjahan McCaskill were chatting in Jackson&#39;s Hyundai Sonata, still on a postvacation high, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.inquirer.com/news/west-philadelphia-shootings-homicide-rates-instagram-feuds-20210316.html">when 24 bullets ripped through the car</a> . The two men, both 26, had been close friends since preschool. They&#39;d just returned to West Philadelphia after a few days hang gliding, zip-lining, and hiking in Puerto Rico. Jackson was parked outside his mom&#39;s house when a black SUV pulled up and the people inside started shooting. Both he and McCaskill were pronounced dead at the hospital.<br><br> In the aftermath, McCaskill&#39;s mother, Najila Zainab Ali McCaskill, couldn&#39;t fathom why anyone would want to kill her son and his friend. Both had beaten the odds for young Black men in their neighborhood and graduated from college. Jackson had been a mental-health technician in an adolescent psych ward while her son had run a small cleaning business and tended bar. She wondered if they&#39;d been targeted by a disgruntled former employee of the cleaning business. But then the police explained: Her son and his friend had been killed because of a clash on social media among some teenagers they&#39;d never even met.<br><br> For months, a battle had been raging on Instagram between crews based on either side of Market Street. Theirs was a long-running rivalry, but a barrage of online taunts and threats had raised tensions in the neighborhood. Police had assigned an officer to monitor the social-media activity of various crews in the city, and the department suspected that the Northsiders in the SUV had mistaken one of the two friends for a rival Southsider and opened fire. An hour after the shooting, a Northsider posted a photo on Instagram with a caption that appeared to mock the victims and encourage the rival crew to collect their bodies: “AHH HAAAA Pussy Pick Em Up!!”<br><br> Jackson and McCaskill died in the first year of a nationwide resurgence in violence that has erased more than two decades of gains in public safety. In 2020, homicides spiked by 30 percent and fluctuated around that level for the next two years. There are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/us-murder-rate-decline-crime-statistics/674290/">early signs</a> that the 2023 rate could show a decrease of more than 10 percent from last year, but that would still leave it well above pre-pandemic levels.<br><br> Criminologists point to a confluence of factors, including the social disruptions caused by COVID‑19, the rise in gun sales early in the pandemic, and the uproar following the murder of George Floyd, which, in many cities, led to diminished police activity and further erosion of trust in the police. But in my reporting on the surge, I kept hearing about another accelerant: social media.<br><br> Violence-prevention workers described feuds that started on Instagram, Snapchat, and other platforms and erupted into real life with terrifying speed. “When I was young and I would get into an argument with somebody at school, the only people who knew about it were me and the people at school,” said James Timpson, a violence-prevention worker in Baltimore. “Not right now. Five hundred people know about it before you even leave school. And then you got this big war going on.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2022/04/american-teens-sadness-depression-anxiety/629524/">Read: Why American teens are so sad</a><br><br> Smartphones and social platforms existed long before the homicide spike; they are obviously not its singular cause. But considering the recent past, it&#39;s not hard to see why social media might be a newly potent driver of violence. When the pandemic led officials to close civic hubs such as schools, libraries, and rec centers for more than a year, people—especially young people—were pushed even further into virtual space. Much has been said about the possible links between heavy social-media use and mental-health problems and suicide among teenagers. Now Timpson and other violence-prevention workers are carrying that concern to the logical next step. If social media plays a role in the rising tendency of young people to harm themselves, could it also be playing a role when they harm others?<br><br> The current spike in violence isn&#39;t a return to &#39;90s-era murder rates—it&#39;s something else entirely. In many cities, the violence has been especially concentrated among the young. The nationwide homicide rate for 15-to-19-year-olds <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/products/databriefs/db471.htm">increased by an astonishing 91 percent</a> from 2014 to 2021. Last year in Washington, DC, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2022/12/31/homicides-dc-va-md-2022/">105 people under 18 were shot</a> —nearly twice as many as in the previous year. In Philadelphia in the first nine months of 2022, the tally of youth shooting victims—181— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/local/philadelphia/2022/10/05/philadelphia-gun-violence-youth-victims">equaled the tally for all of 2015 and 2016 combined</a> . And in Baltimore, more than 60 children ages 13 to 18 were shot in the first half of this year. That&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thebaltimorebanner.com/community/criminal-justice/teen-shootings-gun-violence-baltimore-UW47CTUZVVFCZDMHUVZOY3WGJQ/">double the totals for the first half of each year from 2015 to 2021</a> —and it&#39;s occurred while overall homicides in the city declined. Nationwide, this trend has been racially disproportionate to an extreme degree: In 2021, Black people ages 10 to 24 were <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stacks.cdc.gov/view/cdc/121555">almost 14 times more likely to be the victims of a homicide</a> than young white people.<br><br> Those confronting this scourge—police, prosecutors, intervention workers—are adamant that social-media instigation helps explain why today&#39;s young people are making up a larger share of the victims. But they&#39;re at a loss as to how to combat this phenomenon. They understand that this new wave of killing demands new solutions—but what are they?<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">To the extent</span> that online incitement has drawn attention, it&#39;s been focused on rap videos, particularly those featuring <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vulture.com/article/jayquan-mckenley-chii-wvtzz-eric-adams-drill.html#_ga=2.8250674.1462920847.1690910851-270587328.1687895713">drill music</a> , which started in Chicago in the early 2010s and is dominated by explicit baiting of “opps,” or rivals. These videos have been linked to numerous shootings. Often, though, conflict is sparked by more mundane online activity. Teens bait rivals in Instagram posts or are goaded by allies in private chats. On Instagram and Facebook, they livestream incursions into enemy territory and are met by challenges to “drop a pin”—to reveal their location or be deemed a coward. They brandish guns in Snapchat photos or YouTube and TikTok videos, which might provoke an opp to respond—and pressure the person with the gun to actually use it.<br><br> “If you&#39;re not monitoring social media, you&#39;re wondering why 1,000 people are suddenly downtown fighting.”<br><br> In December, I met 21-year-old Brandon Olivieri at the state prison in Houtzdale, Pennsylvania, where he is serving time for murder. In 2017, Olivieri says, he had a run-in with other teens in South Philadelphia after he tried to sell marijuana on their turf. Later, in a private Instagram chat for Olivieri and his friends, someone posted a picture of a silver .45-caliber pistol. Then another member, Nicholas Torelli, posted a picture of cat feces on the sidewalk, with the caption “Brandon took a shit on opp territory.” It was a joke, but the conversation quickly turned aggressive. Later that day, Olivieri asked Torelli to drop an image of their opponents into the chat, so everyone could see what they looked like. Torelli complied, and, according to court records, Olivieri replied that he would “pop all of them.”<br><br> When Olivieri, Torelli, and two friends encountered four of their opponents later that month, there were heated words, a struggle, and three gunshots from the silver pistol. One bullet struck Caleer Miller, a member of Olivieri&#39;s group. Another hit Salvatore DiNubile, in the other crew. Both died; they were 16. Olivieri was convicted of first-degree murder in DiNubile&#39;s death and third-degree murder in Miller&#39;s. (Torelli testified against Olivieri and was not charged.) Olivieri was sentenced to 37 years to life.<br><br> DiNubile&#39;s father, also named Salvatore, believes the ability to share threats online encouraged Olivieri and his friends to make them; having made them, they felt compelled to follow through. “You said you were gonna do this guy. Here&#39;s your chance,” he told me. “You try to live up to this gangster mentality that he&#39;s self-created.” Olivieri maintains his innocence and says that he wasn&#39;t the one who fired the fatal shots, but he agreed that he and his friends often hyped one another up by making boasts online. “It&#39;s what we call pump-faking,” he explained.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">Last year,</span> as the number of juvenile shooting victims in Washington, DC, climbed toward triple digits, the city&#39;s Peace Academy, which trains community members in violence prevention, held a Zoom session dedicated to social media. Ameen Beale of the DC Attorney General&#39;s Office shared his screen to display a sequence typical of online flare-ups culminating in a fatality.<br><br> The presentation started with a photo, posted to Instagram in 2019, showing the local rapper AhkDaClicka on the Metro; the caption mocked him for being caught there, without a gun, by adversaries. Then came a screenshot of private messages between AhkDaClicka and a rival rapper named Walkdown Will that the latter posted derisively on Instagram Live. Next, an Instagram Story from AhkDaClicka insulting another rapper who had allegedly been present at the Metro run-in, and a YouTube video of AhkDaClicka <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PFxpUO0J9E4">rapping about the incident</a> , including the line “Just give me a Glock and point me to the opps.” Soon afterward, in January 2020, AhkDaClicka was fatally shot. He was 18; his real name was Malick Cisse. That May, police arrested Walkdown Will—William Whitaker, also 18. He pleaded guilty to second-degree murder last October.<br><br> Beale&#39;s presentation left some participants dumbfounded. “I cannot believe the level of immaturity and stupidity that&#39;s become the norm,” one wrote in the chat. Another asked the question looming over the session: Had anyone in the city&#39;s violence-prevention realm asked the social-media companies to limit inflammatory content?<br><br> “I don&#39;t think we&#39;ve made much progress,” Beale admitted. When the city had sought to have posts removed, he said, the companies had rebuffed its pleas with vague arguments about free speech. Even if social-media platforms did remove a post, 20 people could already have shared it with hundreds or thousands more. And given the pace of online life, you might spend five years trying to block harmful content on one platform, only for all the activity to migrate to another.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/social-media-teen-mental-health-crisis-research-limitations/674371/">Read: No one knows exactly what social media is doing to teens</a><br><br> I asked a spokesperson for Google, which owns YouTube, about the AhkDaClicka video with the line about the Glock, as well as another video posted last summer, titled “Pull Da Plug.” It showed a Louisville, Kentucky, rapper and about a dozen other young men apparently celebrating a shooting that had left a man on life support (he later died). The head of the Louisville violence-prevention agency had told me that the victim&#39;s family asked Google to remove the video, but it stayed up, collecting more than 15,000 views. The spokesperson, Jack Malon, told me the company generally had a “pretty high threshold” for determining that music videos were inciting violence, in part because company policy <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://support.google.com/youtube/answer/2802268#zippy=%2Cother-types-of-content-that-violate-this-policy">allows exceptions for artistic content</a> .<br><br> My conversations with Malon and his counterparts at Snap and Meta (which owns Facebook and Instagram) left me with the impression that social-media platforms have given relatively little thought to their role in fueling routine gun violence, compared with the higher-profile debate over censoring incendiary political speech. Meta pointed me to its “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://transparency.fb.com/en-gb/policies/community-standards">community standards</a> ,” which are full of gray-area statements such as “We also try to consider the language and context in order to distinguish casual statements from content that constitutes a credible threat to public or personal safety.” Snap argued that its platform was more benign than others, because posts are designed to disappear and are viewed primarily by one&#39;s friends. I also reached out to TikTok, but the company didn&#39;t respond.<br><br> Communities, meanwhile, have been left to fend for themselves. But violence-prevention groups are dominated by middle-aged men who grew up in the pre-smartphone era; they&#39;re more comfortable intervening in person than deciphering threats on TikTok. Before the pandemic, an intern at Pittsburgh&#39;s main anti-violence organization scanned social-media posts by young people considered at risk of becoming involved in conflicts. The Reverend Cornell Jones, the city government&#39;s liaison to violence-prevention groups, told me that the intern had once detected a feud brewing online among teenagers, some of whom had acquired firearms. Jones brought in the participants and their mothers and defused the situation. Then the intern left town for law school and the organization reverted to the ad hoc methods that are more typical for such groups. “If you&#39;re not monitoring social media, you&#39;re wondering why 1,000 people are suddenly downtown fighting,” Jones said ruefully. In early July, a shooting at a block party in Baltimore validated his concern: Though the event had been discussed widely on social media, no police officers were on hand; later, a video circulated of a teenager showing off what appeared to be a gun at the party. The shooting left two dead and 28 others wounded.<br><br> A decade ago, Desmond Upton Patton, a professor of social policy, communications, and psychiatry at the University of Pennsylvania, got the first of several grants to study what he called “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0747563212003779">internet banging</a> .” His research team co-designed algorithms with a team at Columbia University to analyze language, images, and even emoji on Twitter and identify users at risk of harming themselves or others. The algorithms showed promise in identifying escalating online disputes. But he never allowed their use, worried about their resemblance to police surveillance efforts that had enabled profiling more than prevention. “Perhaps there is a smarter person who can figure out how to do it ethically,” he said to me.<br><br> For now, the system is failing to anticipate violence—and even, quite often, to convict people whose social-media feeds incriminate them. In May, three teens were tried for the murders of Jarell Jackson and Shahjahan McCaskill in Philadelphia. At the time of the shooting, two were 17 and the third was 16. Social-media activity formed a key part of the prosecutors&#39; evidence: Instagram posts and video feeds showed the three defendants driving around in a black SUV seemingly identical to the one that had pulled up alongside Jackson&#39;s car. Other posts showed two of them holding a gun that matched the description of one used in the shooting. After a day of deliberations, the jury acquitted them of murder, finding two of the defendants guilty only of weapons charges. The verdict left the victims&#39; families reeling. “For me and my family, [the trial] was like a seven-day funeral,” Monique Jackson, Jarell&#39;s mother, told me. Afterward, the detective who had investigated the murders speculated to her that jurors on such cases often struggle to grasp the basic mechanics of social media and how essential it is to the interactions of young people. As Patton put it to me, “What we underestimate time and time again is that social media isn&#39;t virtual versus real life. This <i>is</i> life.”<br><br> <em><small>This article has been updated to clarify YouTube&#39;s policy for determining which videos are removed for inciting violence.</small></em><br><br> <small><em>This article is a collaboration between</em> The Atlantic <em>and ProPublica. It appears in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/toc/2023/09">September 2023</a> print edition with the headline “Killer Apps.”</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/jarell-jackson-shahjahan-mccaskill-killed-philadelphia-social-media/674760/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/jarell-jackson-shahjahan-mccaskill-killed-philadelphia-social-media/674760/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Mike Pence’s 11th Commandment]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>你可以说特朗普的坏话，但要小心。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/cTTxI1FB31U4Xhlmi-d3uh0WYyc=/0x0:5693x3202/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/GettyImages_1552040644/original.jpg" alt="迈克·彭斯在舞台上" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>安娜摇钱树/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>罗纳德·里根的第十一条诫命是：“不得说任何共和党同胞的坏话。”这个周末，迈克·彭斯——像大多数共和党人一样——极力批评唐纳德·特朗普，但几乎没有提及特朗普的名字。<br><br>首先，这是来自<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的三个新故事：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/black-folk-book-working-class-blair-lm-kelley/674935/">Ibram X. Kendi：<i>工人阶级</i>不等于<i>白人</i>。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/">特朗普的表现就像他已经走投无路了</a><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/">。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/addiction-drug-policy-language-harm-evidence/674907/">举证责任由语言警察承担。</a></li><strong>害怕说出他的名字</strong><br><br>让我们提醒自己，要好好赞扬迈克·彭斯（Mike Pence）。他不仅在 2021 年 1 月 6 日履行了宪法义务，从而避免了美国政府的崩溃和可能随之而来的流血事件，而且最近他似乎正在大力批评他担任副总统的人。然而，和许多其他共和党领袖一样，彭斯似乎受到了一种死灵法师的诅咒，当他试图说出唐纳德·特朗普的名字时，他冒着被打哑的风险。<br><br>昨天，哥伦比亚广播公司记者加勒特少校<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mike-pence-face-the-nation-aug-6-2023-transcript/">询问彭斯</a>是否仍会投票给特朗普。这是一个将垒球击出公园的机会。相反，他连击了。<br><br><p><b>加勒特少校：</b>你会再次投票给唐纳德·特朗普吗？</p><p><b>迈克·彭斯：</b>听着，我认为我不必这么做。我必须告诉你，无论我走到哪里——</p><p><b>加勒特：</b>副总统先生，这不是问题所在。你会再次投票给唐纳德·特朗普吗？</p><p><b>彭斯：</b>是的。是的，我知道你的问题是什么，但让我说得非常清楚：我竞选总统是因为我认为任何把自己置于宪法之上的人都不应该成为总统，也不应该再次成为总统。</p>嗯，这是一种方法。另一种说法是，“从个人经验来看，唐纳德·特朗普是椭圆形办公室里最危险的人，我将尽一切努力阻止他。”值得称赞的是，彭斯在 1 月 6 日开始采访时，用了足够长的时间使用特朗普的名字，并表示他“错了”。彭斯说，特朗普“那天要求我把他置于宪法之上，但我选择了宪法，而且我永远都会选择。”当被问及是否会作证反对特朗普时，彭斯再次呜咽道：“我没有计划作证，但人们可以相信我们会遵守法律。如果法律的召唤到来，我们将做出回应，而且我们只会说出真相。”<br><br>这并不是令人惊叹的反抗。我们也不应该对一位美国政客声称他将履行他过去多次宣誓的宪法誓言过分印象深刻。但在这个奇怪的时代，我们会采取我们能得到的东西。尽管如此，彭斯显然对这个问题感到不舒服，并尽一切努力将特朗普的名字排除在讨论之外，当你领导一场针对自己前竞选搭档的竞选活动时，这是一件奇怪的事情。<br><br>同样，考虑一下罗恩·德桑蒂斯 (Ron DeSantis) 勉强接受特朗普输掉 2020 年大选的事实。 “他当然输了，”德桑蒂斯今天在接受 NBC 新闻<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/video/-of-course-he-lost-ron-desantis-rejects-trump-s-2020-election-claims-190139973789">采访</a>时说道。 “乔·拜登是总统。”那么特朗普关于选举的谎言呢？ “未经证实，”佛罗里达州州长<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/04/us/politics/desantis-trump-election-2020.html">周五表示</a>。德桑蒂斯一直<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2024-election/ron-desantis-of-course-trump-lost-2020-election-rcna98200">坚持</a>认为 2024 年的选举应该以乔·拜登为主题，但他似乎不愿意面对这样的现实：要挑战拜登就必须先击败特朗普。 <i>《纽约时报》的</i>一篇报道<i> </i><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/07/us/politics/desantis-trump-2020-election.html">将</a>NBC 的评论称为“先生”。德桑蒂斯日益激进的立场”，如果你认为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/07/19/desantis-jan-6-trump/">从“无”到“有”的转变</a>是“越来越激进”，我认为这是正确的。<br><br>为什么共和党人如此害怕提及特朗普，即使是在这么晚的时候？原因有三个，其中两个是出于纯粹的怯懦，第三个则源于幻觉的主要策略。<br><br>对于共和党候选人来说，第一个也是最明显的问题是，对特朗普咆哮会激怒共和党的选民，他们中的许多人居住在共和党关心的地区和州。克里斯·克里斯蒂和阿萨·哈钦森愿意追随特朗普，因为他们都是脸皮厚的人，但也因为他们几乎没有机会获得共和党提名。乔治·威尔<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.yahoo.com/george-republican-party-living-fear-182154354.html?guccounter=1&amp;guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAFshqvzmYCDZvo-PSldHCEUCkXZoCz5GQ9F4OUpI7GFYNPMB0Hv2yWkYzZw8liIlhcrnqdXhB55EmYrN8J_o--wzM26iKsfIhVmDy9VloPQqJHz5v7NSirjb-hVeB5QgSshUsswyNWgNhFai3OCiOOPhywR-0IlhUDtVQpFsrLyx">首先说了这句话</a>，但值得重复一遍：现代共和党是第一个害怕自己选民的美国政党。<br><br>很少有候选人愿意反对特朗普，然后忍受他的恶毒攻击，这是可以理解的，但很难说是领导力的例子。 （特朗普<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/news/2023/08/05/trump-pence-has-gone-to-the-dark-side-00109960">已经在他的社交媒体平台Truth Social上抨击了</a>“Liddle”[<i>原文如此</i>]迈克·彭斯（Mike Pence），指责他是一个忘恩负义的失败者，“走向了黑暗面”。）特朗普对此感到震惊，当他瞄准他所认为的敌人时，他的攻击造成了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/threats-follow-trump-poliical-attacks/2020/10/28/c6dbce02-1792-11eb-82db-60b15c874105_story.html">真正的安全问题</a>：看看纽约付出了多少努力；华盛顿特区; <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2023/07/31/georgia-2020-election-investigation-trump/">显然，亚特兰大</a>不得不承诺起诉或准备起诉特朗普。<br><br>然而，即使在不那么可怕的层面上，竞选总统——或者试图团结共和党剩下的人——也没有人会因为与特朗普无脑争吵而感到头疼。从德桑蒂斯和彭斯往下，共和党阵营都避免提及特朗普的名字，把他（正如<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/peacefield/61a69df40b037b002073ccd5/fight-like-adults/">我在 2021 年所写的</a>那样）视为某种古老的神或神秘的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://en.natmus.dk/historical-knowledge/denmark/middle-ages-1000-1536/j-r-r-tolkien/balrog-medieval-monsters/">炎魔</a>，一提到他的名字就会出现并引发混乱。<br><br>最后，共和党初选候选人似乎都有一个由虚荣驱动的信念，即一旦特朗普因法律问题退出竞选，或者当其他不可抗力使他脱离董事会时，他们每个人都可以继承特朗普的选民。在某个地方，有一位战略家告诉他的客户，<i>如果不是特朗普</i>，<i> </i>选民会蜂拥而至，比如妮基·哈利 (Nikki Haley) 或维韦克·拉马斯瓦米 (Vivek Ramaswamy)。这就是《<i>堡垒》</i>作家蒂姆·米勒所说<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thetriad.thebulwark.com/p/ron-desantiss-prisoners-dilemma">的</a>“一场幻想初选”，这场初选是在“暗中厌恶特朗普的共和党精英的头脑中举行的，他们希望选民很快就会清醒过来”并选择其他人。<br><br>现在，确实，如果特朗普身体丧失行为能力——我不希望这位前总统有任何健康问题——那么，是的，共和党人将不得不寻找其他人。然而，除此之外，即使特朗普被监禁，他显然也会参选。 （没有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2021/05/can-trump-run-for-president-from-prison.html">法律或宪法规则</a>阻止这种尝试。）他将继续攻击美国机构，他将继续发出几乎不加掩饰的暴力威胁， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/03/23/indictment-looms-trump-criticizes-calls-peace/">正如他一再所做的那样</a>， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/legal/trumps-threatening-post-flagged-by-us-prosecutors-judge-2023-08-05/">即使是在被起诉的情况下</a>。<br><br>与此同时，其他共和党人无法说出特朗普的名字，无法以他不适合担任公职为由起诉他，也无法让共和党选民了解他涉嫌的任何犯罪活动。早在三月份， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/mike-pence-trump-january-6/673402/">我就曾写道</a>，彭斯“只有这一刻的勇气，不会再有其他的了。”不幸的是，我是对的。此时，其他共和党人在进入 2024 年时将无法模仿彭斯唯一的正派日子。<br><br><b>有关的：</b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/mike-pence-trump-january-6/673402/">迈克·彭斯正在警告我们有关特朗普的事情。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-lead-lincoln-dinner/674877/">特朗普的必然性问题</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>Tou Thao 是一名前警官，因参与杀害乔治·弗洛伊德而被定罪，被州法院<a href="https://apnews.com/article/george-floyd-minneapolis-officer-tou-thou-sentencing-586deaeb4d14807ef3f2bdd0196d0b86">判处</a>近五年监禁。</li><li>乌克兰声称<a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/zelenskyy-assassination-plot-ukraine-detains-russia-informant-rcna98507">已拘留了</a>一名俄罗斯线人，称该线人参与了通过空袭刺杀总统泽连斯基的明显阴谋。</li><li>阿拉斯加朱诺市官员昨天<a href="https://www.axios.com/2023/08/07/record-glacial-flooding-juneau-alaska-emergency-declaration">宣布进入紧急状态</a>，因为创纪录的冰川湖洪水摧毁了至少两座建筑物。</li><b>晚读</b><br><br>孤独的武器化<br><br><em>希拉里·罗德姆·克林顿</em><br><br><p>在过去八年的大部分时间里，我和其他许多人关注的问题是，我们的民主为何变得如此容易受到潜在的强人和煽动者的影响。现在让我彻夜难眠的问题——随着 2024 年的临近，这一问题变得越来越紧迫——是我们在重建防御方面是否做了足够的努力，或者我们的民主是否仍然很容易受到攻击和颠覆。</p><p>我们有理由担心：黑钱和企业势力的影响、右翼宣传和错误信息、外国对我们选举的恶意干涉，以及对社会进步的强烈反对。多年来，“巨大的右翼阴谋”一直引起我的极大兴趣。但我长期以来一直认为，我们关于民主受到威胁的全国性对话中遗漏了一些重要的东西。现在，来自一个也许出人意料的来源——美国顶级医生——的最新发现为我们的问题提供了新的视角，并为我们如何开始治愈我们患病的国家提供了宝贵的见解。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/hillary-clinton-essay-loneliness-epidemic/674921/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/freedom-to-read-pen-america-censorship/674936/">对知识自由的三种攻击</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/ai-chatgpt-college-essay-plagiarism/674928/">人工智能学院即将迎来第二年。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/viktor-orban-illiberalism-ron-desantis-universities/674915/">为什么民粹右翼讨厌大学</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/electric-vehicle-energy-infrastructure-heat-waves/674940/">德克萨斯州是对驾驶未来的展望。</a></li><strong>文化突破</strong><br><br><b>读。</b>在这个分散注意力的时代，这里有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/attention-focus-book-recommendations/674941/">七本书</a>会让你放下手机。<br><br><b>手表。</b><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Im-A-Virgo-Season-1/dp/B0B8PXXV2M"><i>我是处女座</i></a><i> </i>（在亚马逊 Prime Video 上播放）是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/boots-riley-virgo-show-recommendation/674933/">一部甜蜜、超现实主义的成长剧集</a>，讲述了一名 13 英尺高的黑人男子被家人隐藏起来，直到他最终逃脱的故事。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br><b>聚苯乙烯</b><br><br>当你在杂志社工作时，人们会向你发送一些东西，例如总统竞选的公告。这就是我知道史蒂夫·拉菲正在竞选总统的原因。<br><br>我以当地人的自豪感注意到拉菲是罗德岛州克兰斯顿的前市长，这座城市距离我在海洋州居住的地方不远。 （我从未见过他；这个州可没<i>那么</i>小。）他曾担任过一届市长，并于 2006 年竞选美国参议员，但失败了。 2010年，他差点竞选罗德岛州州长；相反，他搬到了科罗拉多州，参加了 2013 年的州长竞选，然后退出了州长竞选，然后试图在 2014 年获得科罗拉多州第四国会选区的共和党提名（但失败了）。<br><br>那时我不太关注当地政治，所以我无法真正判断拉菲当市长是否出色。但他似乎是对新英格兰共和党财政保守和社会温和传统的倒退，这种传统在共和党中几乎已经绝迹。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/meet-steve-laffey-longest-long-shot-candidates/story?id=101554970">据</a>美国广播公司新闻报道，拉菲几乎没有钱，也没有亚原子民意调查数字——他还没有参加全国民意调查——所以他不太可能有资格参加共和党辩论。这太糟糕了，因为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.stevelaffey.com/about.html">他的口号之一</a>是：“我为克兰斯顿做到了，我将为美国做到了”，这有点迷人，我希望看到唐纳德·特朗普甚至试图通过侮辱美国来反驳这一点。克兰斯顿的好人民和好城市。<br><br> — 汤姆<br><br><i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br><em>当您使用本新闻通讯中的链接购买书籍时，我们会收到佣金。感谢您对大西洋月刊的支持</em><em>。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 22:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/mike-pence-trump-comments-2024-election/674948/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/mike-pence-trump-comments-2024-election/674948/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump Is Acting Like He’s Cornered]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The former president&#39;s response to the latest indictment suggests a man rattled in a way he seldom has been before. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rn9qeKhbA3Ed8QcVbC6TwdHXfyQ=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/trump-1/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普，从后面看" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>克里斯托弗·阿卢卡·贝里/路透社</figcaption></figure>在某些方面，唐纳德·特朗普的精神状态比几乎任何公众人物都更加透明：他没有羞耻感，缺乏自由裁量权，并且有充足的渠道来实时表达他的感受。然而，他持续不断的意识流和始终高度的愤怒使他很难解析他情绪中的细微波动。<br><br>即便如此，自特别检察官杰克·史密斯<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trump-indicted-january-6-jack-smith/674886/">上周起诉前总统以来，这位前总统的公开行为表明他</a>感到被逼入绝境。这并不是说特朗普<em>被逼</em>入绝境——他摆脱困境的能力让<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newsweek.com/cats-nine-lives-myth-explained-1643381">每只家猫都</a>羡慕他——但他对案件的处理表明，他以一种前所未有的方式惊慌失措。<br><br>这位前总统攻击史密斯的措辞极其个人化，甚至对他来说也是如此。他还攻击了负责审理此案的联邦法官坦尼娅·楚特坎(Tanya Chutkan)。他在阿拉巴马州和南卡罗来纳州发表了愤怒的演讲。他嘲笑美国女足国家队，指责乔·拜登总统提前退出世界杯， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110842705795010789">莫名其妙地嘲笑</a>前众议院议长南希·佩洛西（“她是一个邪恶的女巫，她丈夫的地狱之旅从她开始，到她结束。她是一个生病和精神错乱的精神病人，有一天会生活在地狱里！”）。他派他的律师去制作所有五个主要的周日早间电视节目。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thedailybeast.com/theres-a-good-reason-trump-aides-dont-think-the-new-indictment-is-a-joke?ref=home?ref=home?ref=home"><em>《每日野兽报》</em>采访了</a>特朗普内部人士，他们报告称特朗普阵营内部存在严重担忧。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trump-indicted-january-6-jack-smith/674886/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：特朗普试图对美国民主进行公然、极其严重的攻击</a><br><br>但他和他的盟友都没有对他的行为提供连贯的描述，这表明他没有密谋推翻正式选举产生的政府。这可能是因为他密谋推翻正式选举产生的政府。<br><br> “精神错乱的杰克·史密斯正在他的头号选秀权、他的‘梦想’的法官（他必须被撤职！）面前，试图剥夺我的第一修正案权利——尽管事实上他，司法部，和他的许多暴徒检察官，正在非法向假新闻媒体泄露一切！” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110848362917019858">特朗普今天早上在他的真相社交网站上写道</a>。<br><br>这条消息是在最近几天发生的一系列其他咆哮之后发出的，包括对前副总统迈克·彭斯的攻击（“小个子”迈克·彭斯，一个即将被罢免印第安纳州州长职务的人，直到我出现并任命他为副总统，他已经去了黑暗面”）和 Chutkan（“当法官“分配”到可笑的言论自由/公平选举案件时，我不可能得到公平的审判”）。<br><br>通常不建议将攻击案件中的法官和检察官作为辩护策略，但特朗普对礼貌、礼貌或基本常识没有什么用处。史密斯显然正在注意；检察官在法庭文件中引用了社交媒体上一条含糊威胁的帖子，该帖子发布几小时后。 （消息称：“如果你追我，我就追你！”；特朗普发言人声称，这实际上是针对“绿诺集团、热爱中国、不诚实的特殊利益集团和超级政治行动委员会”。）特朗普对查特坎的猛烈抨击，查特坎是一位黑人奥巴马任命的人，他甚至还没有机会在此案中做出任何重大决定，而他对艾琳·坎农法官缺乏批评，艾琳·坎农是特朗普任命的法官，负责监督佛罗里达州的案件，因为他对机密处理不当。文件，如果不令人惊讶的话，也是值得注意的。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trump-indictment-gop-jan-6/674895/">罗纳德·布朗斯坦：特朗普对民主的威胁现在是系统性的</a><br><br>辨别特朗普的煽动行为很容易。确定他爆发的目标并不那么简单。一种解释是，他试图刺激史密斯的团队，将其成员从检察官变成迫害者，引诱他们反应过度或要求苛刻的条件，而特朗普可以利用这些条件要求改变审判地点或对定罪提出上诉。但这让人想起<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/profit"><em>《南方公园》</em>中的内裤侏儒模因</a>：第一步和期望的结果很清楚，但中间的步骤可能是什么却完全神秘。尽管特朗普称史密斯“精神错乱”，但这位特别检察官却显得异常、甚至不可思议地冷漠。与其他特区法官一样，Chutkan 驳回了之前关于 1 月 6 日审判无法在该地区公平进行的说法。<br><br>另一种理论认为，特朗普只是在迎合公众舆论，而不是法院。昨天，特朗普的律师约翰·劳罗(John Lauro)在周日节目中巡回演出，这一策略被环城公路的书呆子们称为“完整的金斯伯格”(Full Ginsburg)，以莫妮卡·莱温斯基(Monica Lewinsky)的律师威廉·金斯伯格(William Ginsburg)的名字命名，后者率先回应有关他的客户与时任总统比尔关系的报道。克林顿.这是一种强大的公共关系工具——例如<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Full_Ginsburg">总统候选人使用的工具</a>——但作为审前策略却有些令人困惑。<br><br>特朗普通常更感兴趣的是唤醒他的支持者，而不是寻求谨慎的辩护，显然他认为，无论他在法律方面存在什么问题，他的政治影响力都足以逃避或至少巧妙地应对危险。在针对他的两起联邦案件中，他可能最终面临不那么容易规避的指控，但他的反应不一定跟上。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/jeffrey-clark-doj-weaponization-trump-indictment/674898/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：司法部的真正武器化</a><br><br>在某种程度上，公关攻势可能正在发挥作用。根据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-indictment-jan-6-opinion-poll-2023-08-06/">哥伦比亚广播公司新闻/YouGov 的一项新民意调查</a>，超过一半的美国人认为对特朗普的指控旨在损害他的 2024 年竞选活动，尽管绝大多数人也认为这些指控是为了维护法治和捍卫民主。但劳罗在电视上提出的实际论点似乎并不是特别精心设计，而且似乎反而强化了这样一个现实：无论公众是否希望他被定罪，他们都对特朗普试图窃取选举结果感到震惊。<br><br>劳罗在不同场合辩称，特朗普所谓的行为是“有抱负的”。例如，“特朗普总统没有做的是指示副总统彭斯做任何事情，”劳罗在美国有线电视新闻网 (CNN) 上说道。 “他以一种渴望的方式问他。”他还称特朗普要求佐治亚州国务卿布拉德·拉芬斯佩格“找到 11,780 票”是一个“雄心勃勃的要求”。这种毫无区别的区分给律法主义带来了坏名声。劳罗还表示，即使特朗普“技术上违反了宪法”，他也没有犯罪。 But telling the public that your client violated the Constitution seems like a questionable PR decision.<br><br> Neither Lauro, in his five appearances, nor Trump, going back to his initial response to the indictment, has actually rebutted the charges. Trump has claimed that the government is attacking his right to free speech, but he has made nearly no effort to question the specifics of the charges. A rare example is his denial of Pence&#39;s claim that Trump said he was “too honest.” More broadly, Trump hasn&#39;t offered any bigger explanation for his weeks-long push to subvert the election. If Trump is acting as though he&#39;s cornered, that is because he doesn&#39;t have a good answer to this question.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 19:37:08 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/</item></channel></rss>